<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Banks Stand to Lose One Billion Pounds in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 30 (Xinhua) - Banks in Britain stand to lose
more than one billion pounds (1.6 billion US dollars) in bad debts
as the Asian economic crisis spreads around the world.
</P>
<P>
They have an estimated 50 billion pounds (80 billion US
dollars) in loans to the region, figures from the Bank of England
show.
</P>
<P>
City analysts predict that the huge figures will force the
banks to allow for the heavy write-offs as their borrowers become
unable to repay.
</P>
<P>
Royal Bank of Scotland has already led the way by announcing a
12 million pounds (19.2 million US dollars) provision against bad
and doubtful loans in Thailand, though the final figure is
expected to be much higher.
</P>
<P>
Much larger write-offs are expected from other banks, including
the mighty HSBC which may write off up to 600 million pounds (960
million US dollars). Standard Chartered is looking at provisions
of at least 250 million pounds (400 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Other leading banks have yet to disclose how much they will
have to write off, but analysts believe it could be in the region
of 90 million pounds (144 million US dollars) for NatWest, 60
million pounds (96 million US dollars) for Barclays and 10 million
pounds (16 million US dollars) at Abbey National (one of Britain's
building societies).
</P>
<P>
One analyst said: "It is too soon to assess the full impact,
but a write-off of about 1 percent of exposure seems reasonable at
this stage." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
