<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharif Vows to Purge Pakistan of Corruption, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif said today the country's constitutional crisis was
created out of petty issues and vowed "to rid the country of
corruption, terrorism and lawlessness."
</P>
<P>
In a nationwide TV and Radio broadcast here this evening,
Sharif, in power for nine months, said that "a stable government
has been plunged into an atmosphere of uncertainty owing to the
wishes of a few people."
</P>
<P>
The present crisis surfaced soon after a deterrent law was
passed by the Parliament to curb terrorism in the country, Sharif
said in his 25-minute speech, referring to the on-going power
tussle between the executive and the judiciary involving him and
Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah.
</P>
<P>
"The present uncertain conditions have nothing to do either
with problems of the people or with the integrity of the country,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that nothing could obstruct him from completing "my
mission to purge the society of its presents ills."
</P>
<P>
The economy which was put back on track from the brink of
bankruptcy, he stated, was losing one billion rupees (about 20
million U.S. dollars) everyday, adding that foreign exchange which
registered an improvement after his take over has again lost 200
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
"This was the greatest injustice to the 140 million people who
gave him the mandate to complete his mission," he said, noting
that undue hurdles have been created in the completion of his
mission.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, he will not allow the masses to fall victims
to conspiracies.
</P>
<P>
"It is my obligation to protect the country and its
constitution," he declared.  
</P>
</TEXT>
