<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Calls for Controls After CJD Transplant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, November 30 (Xinhua) -- British government is calling
for tighter transplant checks after tissue from the eyes of a
woman with CJD, or human equivalency of mad cow disease, was
transplanted into three other people.
</P>
<P>
Marion Hamilton, 53, who died of lung cancer, was later found
to have CJD, the BBC television reported today.
</P>
<P>
The information was reportedly not passed on to doctors
supervising the transplants.
</P>
<P>
The fatal disease may be infected by contacting any tissue from
the patient.
</P>
<P>
Scottish health minister Sam Galbraith said every effort would
be made to improve procedure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
