<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's BJP Party Stakes Claim to Form Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The Hindu nationalist party
Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) and its allies today staked their
claim to form a government, Press Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
After a 35-minute meeting with President Kocheril Raman
Narayanan here this evening, BJP President L.K. Advani, when asked
if the party had formally staked its claim, responded that "in a
way it can be called as staking claim."
</P>
<P>
Advani's response assumed significance because the BJP, the
largest party in the parliament, has been very cautious in staking
claim to form a government since the United Front government
collapsed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The minority government led by Prime Minister Inder Kumar
Gujral fell after the Congress party withdrew support to it over
an investigative report on the assassination of former prime
minister Rajiv Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
Advani told reporters that President Narayanan had assured the
delegation of opposition parties that he would not take a "hasty"
decision and holding of fresh elections would be the last resort.
</P>
<P>
The BJP president said the formation of a majority government
in the present situation "does not seem to be feasible on paper"
but it could be possible after a realignment of political parties.
</P>
<P>
Apart from his meeting with the opposition parties, President
Narayanan is expected to meet leaders of the United Front and the
Congress party on Monday as part of his consultation efforts to
find a way out of the current political impasse in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Congress party has claimed to form a coalition of its own
immediately after its withdrawal of support to the Gujral
government on Friday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
