<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 42 Billion Dollars For UAE's Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates has
pumped more than 42 billion U.S. dollars over the past four years
to develop its economy.
</P>
<P>
According to a report today, the total sum includes both public
and private investments between 1993 to 1997. Investment in the
oil sector accounted for nearly one fifth of the total funding.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources said that the funds invested in the oil sector
were used to maintain and develop existing onshore and offshore
oil fields to boost capacity and meet growing global crude demand.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the other capitals, estimated at some 33.6 billion
dollars, was invested in manufacturing, agriculture and public
service sectors to diversify the country's income resources, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The UAE's revenues are heavily reliant on oil earnings which
account for nearly two thirds of its total incomes each year.
</P>
<P>
The UAE government launched an economic diversification campaign
from early 1990 and has made "great achievements." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
