<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak PM Accuses President of Not Extending Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif today accused the Presidency of not extending
cooperation in the parliament's efforts to preserve the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
In his televised address to the nation this evening, Prime
Minister Sharif said that the steps taken by the Presidency in the
recent days have revealed the real cause of the "hysterical
situation prevailing in the country."
</P>
<P>
Sharif took the nation into confidence on the persisting
constitutional crisis in the country arising out of unprecedented
factionalism in the Judiciary leading to a direct request by Chief
Justice Sajjad Ali Shah to the Army for security of the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
He said that his government passed amendment in the contempt of
court law to steer Pakistan out of the further crisis but
President Farooq Leghari did not sign the bill.
</P>
<P>
"There was nothing bad in the law but it just gave right of
appeal to the aggrieved party," said Sharif, adding that "right of
appeal in superior court has been given against the verdict of
lower courts. Appeal against the Session Court could be filed in
the High Court and appeal in Supreme Court be filed against any
judgment of the High Court."
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that the amendment in the contempt of court law was
in accordance with Islamic principles and any civilized system.
</P>
<P>
"We had given the right to the court to decide on any appeal in
the contempt of court case. Crisis could be averted if the
president signed the bill. However, he refused to sign the law,
passed by the two houses of the parliament," He added.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that "the situation is very unfortunate. The entire
country is in the grip of chaos."
</P>
<P>
He regretted that there is no assistance from the Presidency in
the government's move to save the parliament and constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
