<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Decides to Defer Redeployment (I) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Cabinet decided
today to defer the second troop redeployment in the West Bank
until a ministerial committee formulates a final map on Israeli
interests and the Palestinian side fulfills its peace commitments.
</P>
<P>
A government statement issued after the weekly Cabinet meeting
said the cabinet, in a vote of 16 in favor and two abstentions,
decided in principle to carry out further redeployment.
</P>
<P>
But the extent and timetable for the second redeployment will
only be decided by a ministerial committee headed by Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, which will work out a picture of
Israeli interests on the final-status talks with the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
The two abstained were Transportation Minister Yitzhak Levy and
Education Minister Zevulun Hammer from the rightwing National
Religious Party which opposes any further troop redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The statement conditioned the implementation of further
redeployment on PNA's fulfillment of its commitments, including
completing the process of amending the Palestinian Covenant which
called for Israel's destruction, fighting terrorism and preventing
violence, and keeping the size of Palestinian police according to
the interim agreements.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government urged the PNA to agree to hold the
final-status talks immediately in order to seek a final solution.
"The government believes the proper manner in which to advance the
peace process with the Palestinians is through immediately
entering negotiations regarding the final-status talks," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It noted Israel would soon determine its position on the final
settlement, including a map on various security areas,
settlements, water resources and Jewish historical sites. The map
will be decided by the ministerial committee which also includes
Foreign Minister David Levy, Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
and National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh said after today's meeting that
Israel will begin informing its decision on further redeployment
to other parties concerned with the peace process. Foreign
Minister Director-General Eiitan Bentsur was dispatched to Cairo
today to brief the Egyptian government on the decision.
</P>
<P>
The decision drew fierce criticism from Israel's opposition.
The opposition party Meretz responded with a decision to table a
non-confidence motion in the Kensset (parliament) tomorrow against
the government.
</P>
<P>
Meretz leader Yossi Sarid said his party will not support
Netanyahu's "policy of deception" and only supports concrete
steps taken to advance the peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
