<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-30 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Decides to Defer Redeployment (II) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 30 (Xinhua) --
</P>
<P>
Leading opposition Labor party's lawmaker Yossi Beilin charged
the Netanyahu government of deferring the implementation of its
peace commitments. "They just want to satisfy the right, they
don't think either about the solution, about the peace process,
about the Palestinians, about the Americans or about the peace
camp in Israel," he said.
</P>
<P>
Labor faction head in the Knesset Rannan Cohen also accused
Netanyahu of "being held hostage by a handful of rightist
extremists" by avoiding decision-making on the further
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
PNA officials reacted angrily, accusing the Netanyahu
government of avoiding decision-making and trying to move away
from the peace process. Senior Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat
dismissed the Israeli decision as "too vague, too little and much
too late."
</P>
<P>
Hanan Ashrawi, PNA Minister of Higher Education, denounced the
Israeli move as a violation of all signed peace agreements.
"Actually, this is a non-starter, because obviously the Israeli
government is attempting to outmaneuver the Americans, the
international community, and the Palestinians, and try to deflect
the pressure and demands that Israel adhere to agreements," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past week, Netanyahu met strong opposition within his
hardline rightwing government to his efforts to win support for
his proposal on further redeployment. Today's cabinet decision was
apparently aimed at pleasing the hardliners and designed to show
the government unity on policies toward the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Israel's state television Channel I reported that with the
decision to go ahead with the redeployment, regardless the lack
of a date and extent, Netanyahu believed it will open the door for
a long-delayed summit with United States President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration has been reportedly pressing heavily
on Netanyahu to carry out the redeployment in order to break the
stalemate in the peace process. To express his displeasure with
Israel's handling of the peace process, Clinton refused to meet
Netanyahu during the latter's visit to the U.S. early the
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
