<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-30 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts: New Output Ceiling Depresses Oil Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The new output ceiling set
by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) will
depress crude oil prices on the international market to less than
18 U.S. dollars a barrel in 1998, experts here said today.
</P>
<P>
Ali Akber, marketing manager of the Abu Dhabi National Oil
Company (ADNOC), said that the output increase will deal a severe
blow to oil prices, which fluctuate around 18.5 dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
"I expect prices to be lower than the 18-dollar level next year
because the demand would likely keep unchanged while the supplies
increase," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he is "not optimistic" about OPEC members'
earnings in 1998, because the production increase can not bring
them more profits due to "damaged prices."
</P>
<P>
The OPEC members on Saturday decided to increase their daily
output to a total of 27.5 million barrels, up 10 percent, or 2.5
million barrels from existing oil production quota.
</P>
<P>
Some other experts, however, said that the new quota would
improve the competitive capabilities of OPEC members in the world
oil market.
</P>
<P>
"Actually, the new ceiling will impose negative effects on
crude (oil) prices, but on the other hand, it will make OPEC more
influential in the market," they claimed.
</P>
<P>
Most countries in the Gulf region that form the core of the
organization, have expressed satisfaction with the decision, which
they hope will restore credibility of the OPEC in world oil market.
</P>
<P>
The OPEC includes 12 members of Saudi Arabia, Iran, Iraq,
Qatar, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Venezuela, Indonesia,
Nigeria, Libya, Algeria and Gabon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
