<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Kohl Have Informal Meeting in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today had a 90-minute informal
talks at the presidential residence Rus outside Moscow, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relations Yeltsin and Kohl agreed to hold annual
top-level meetings with key ministers taking part.
</P>
<P>
They considered the ways of setting up three-sided
consultations involving Russia, France and Germany in line with
the wish expressed by French President Jaques Chirac at the EC
summit in Strasbourg, which is planned to be held in
Yekaterinburg, Russia, in the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
At the same time the two leaders discussed the training way for
young Russian managers in Germany in keeping with a recent
initiative by Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed a joint project for creating a European
military transport plane on the basis of AN-70 aircraft, and said
that experts would start consultations on the project in Berlin in
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Among international issues, the leaders highlighted the
situation in the Middle East, voicing anxiety over the lack of
progress in Israeli-Palestinian relations, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Kohl spoke highly of the actions of Yeltsin and Russian
diplomats toward resolving the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
It was earlier reported that Moscow is concerned with
"underdevelopment" of economic contacts between the two states "as
compared with the level of their political cooperation," according
to Russian presidential spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin and Kohl met one day before Russia's partnership and
cooperation agreement with the European Union takes effect.
</P>
<P>
The German Chancellor arrived in Moscow on Sunday mid-day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
