<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lagos Prepares to Increase Water Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The demand for water supply in
Lagos, the largest city and economic center of Nigeria, is expected to
rise to 1,509 million cubic litres per day by the year 2010 with
population projected to be 12.4 million at that time.
</P>
<P>
A report by the Lagos State Water Corporation today said the
current water supply stands at 827 million litres a day, which can
meet only 40 percent of demand.
</P>
<P>
The report attributes to short supply to financial constraints in
the state government and calls for the participation of private
investors to meet and sustain the water needs of the people.
</P>
<P>
Lagos is one of the largest metropolises in Africa, which has a
population of about 10 million and covers an area of 3,577 square
kilometers with 22 percent of lagoons and creeks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
