<HEADLINE> Land Degradation Threatens Cattle Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Science and
Technology Commission has said that land degradation could be the
cause for the loss of 10 percent of the national cattle herd by
the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, Commissioner Asrat
Bulbula said here Saturday at the International Livestock
Research Institute that the problem resulted in a loss of
livestock equivalent to one million tropical livestock units (250
million kilograms)in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Unless arrested, the figure may rise to two million units some
13 years later, he warned.
</P>
<P>
"For the resource-poor rural land users, environmental
implications will mean nothing unless there are alternatives for
sustainable livelihoods," the commissioner noted.
</P>
<P>
He added that livestock development strategies should be
re-oriented toward better use of local resources and contribute
effectively to food security.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia is the biggest animal husbandry nation in Africa
with a total of 130 million domestic animals including 27 million
cattles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
