<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Orphans to Reach 620,000 in Two Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Around 620,000 children
in Ethiopia could become orphans in the coming two years as a
result of the AIDS virus and the number may well reach 1.3
million by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian Vice-Minister of Health Lamisso Hayesso said in a
statement to observe this year's world AIDS campaign which falls
on December 1.
</P>
<P>
Hayesso said a total of 1.7 million AIDS patients were
reported last year while the World Health Organization estimated
the number to be 8.4 million worldwide during the same period.
</P>
<P>
In the situation in Ethiopia, the vice-minister said, AIDS is
spreading at an alarming rate both in the rural and urban areas
and that it will grow even more serious unless strict measures
are taken without delay to counter the menace.
</P>
<P>
The focus of the campaign will be the youth and children under
the age of 18, he said. The campaign aims at reducing
the spread of the disease, providing patients with better care
and medical service and raising public awareness against the
disease, he added.
</P>
<P>
A total of 19,433 AIDS cases were reported to the Ethiopian
Health Ministry in July 1995. The actual number of AIDS
patients, however, was estimated by the ministry to be 350,000.
In 1996, the number of people infected with the HIV-virus was
estimated to be 1.7 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
