<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Current Account Deficit Rises Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Canada's current account deficit
rose sharply to 6.4 billion dollars (4.5 billion US dollars) in
the third quarter, Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
The enlarged deficit was largely the result of decreasing
surplus on trade in goods, the federal statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus fell to 3.7 billion dollars in the third
quarter of 1997 from a peak of 11.7 billion dollars in the second
quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the third quarter, the country's trade surplus fell by 2.1
billion dollars, as imports kept climbing for a fifth consecutive
quarter, rising by a substantial 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, higher profits of Canadian affiliates of
foreign owned companies also contributed to the current account
deficit, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign companies, mainly U.S.-owned, invested 5.0 billion
dollars of direct investment in Canada, their second largest
investment on record.
</P>
<P>
Foreign portfolio investors also bought record Canadian
securities. In the third quarter, they purchased 12.6 billion of
Canadian securities, their fourth largest investment on record.
</P>
</TEXT>
