<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea, IMF Bailout Talks Stalled on Key Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Talks between South Korea and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) on the terms of an IMF rescue
package were stalled on differences over the economic growth rate
and the fate of troubled financial institutions in the Asian
nation.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Ministry of Finance and Economy announced early
today that the ministry and the visiting IMF delegation have
reached a provisional agreement on terms for an emergency bailout
package.
</P>
<P>
Finance and Economy Minister Lim Chang-yuel and IMF Managing
Director Michel Camdessus, however, were not successful in
negotiating the detailed terms of the bailout loan over the phone
later today.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus, who is attending a meeting of finance ministers of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and six other
nations in Kuala Lumpur, flatly denied the South Korean assertion
on a package settlement, according to South Korean officials.
</P>
<P>
In their phone discussions, Camdessus insisted that South Korea
should lower its economic growth rate next year to less than 2.5
percent from the initially-set 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
But Lim called for a minimum expansion of 3 percent, citing
concerns over high unemployment and other damaging effects, a
ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government is also reluctant to accept an IMF
demand for the immediate shutdown of heavily-indebted banks and
merchant banks.
</P>
<P>
Seoul asked the IMF for three to six months to resolve the
ailing banks' problems in accordance with its own program unveiled
in November.
</P>
<P>
Seoul officials fear that a gross domestic product growth of
2.5 percent and the resulting belt-tightening would sharply raise
the nation's jobless rate leading to overall social unrest.
</P>
<P>
Except for these differences, South Korea and the IMF have
reportedly reached a consensus over other macroeconomic goals, the
ministry sources said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to slash South Korea's 1998 current
account deficit of 5 billion U.S. dollars from this year's
projected 13 billion dollars, they said.
</P>
<P>
Other agreed conditions included an increase of the value added
tax from the present 10 percent to 11 percent, a cut of about 7.5
billion dollars in next year's government spending and a decrease
of the annual monetary growth rate from the current 18 percent to
10 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lim Chang-yuel notified the IMF delegation this
afternoon that they are prepared to start anew on a bailout
package on the knotty issues to reach a final agreement.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the South Korean government is likely to accept
some of the IMF's demands on the urgently needed bailout should
the talks reach a deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus told reporters in Kuala Lumpur that the South Koreans
have good reasons to accept the IMF demands since they are in the
interests of their country.
</P>
<P>
The top IMF official said he was hopeful that the discussions
would be concluded this week.
</P>
<P>
As soon as the IMF and South Korea reach the final accord on
the multibillion dollar rescue package, the first installment of
the bailout loan, estimated at about 10 billion dollars, will
arrive in Seoul, ministry officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior CPC Official Points To Need For Democratic System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Wei Jianxing, a member of
the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) Central Committee, has said that a democratic
system needs to be built in rural areas to promote openness.
</P>
<P>
Wei made the remark during an inspection tour of north China's
Hebei province from November 25 to December 1, where he asked village
cadres to make government affairs accessible to the public and
supervised by Party members and farmers.
</P>
<P>
He said that greater openness can help build a democratic
system and increase the cadres' sense of responsibility. Many
problems have been solved and social stability established when
the method has been used in some villages, he said.
</P>
<P>
Village affairs include managing the budget, birth control,
electrical power fees, and grain purchases. Every Chinese village
has a grass-roots government to deal with them.
</P>
<P>
Wei said that if villagers can supervise political affairs in
their own village, then a clean government can be built,
corruption an be stopped, and the Party's style be improved.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that the method reflects a decision on
increasing democracy at the grass-roots level made at the 15th
Party Congress held in last September, and that farmers, who
account for more than 80 percent of the Chinese population, are
its base and that the modernization drive can continue if their
enthusiasm is brought into play.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese provinces have adopted the policy of openness in
their villages and Hebei province is one that has done well in
it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
