<HEADLINE> Pak Presidential Spokesman Describes PM's Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's presidential
spokesman said today that it is "most unfortunate" that Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif has chosen to accuse the president of
conspiring against the government, particularly in matters before
the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Sharif's televised speech to the nation last
night, the spokesman said the people of Pakistan know that
President Farooq Leghari has always held the judiciary in the
highest esteem and consistently fought to respect, protect and
enhance its independence and sanctity.
</P>
<P>
"The President has assiduously followed the constitution and
law at all times. In deed, the president has worked hard to try
and help the government extricate itself from a self-created
mess," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
He explained that President Leghari did not think it
appropriate to offer further comments on the prime minister's
speech at this time when efforts are being made to reunite the
Supreme Court and redress the damage done to it in recent days.
</P>
<P>
In his speech to the nation last night, Prime Minister Sharif
openly accused President Leghari of not extending cooperation in
the parliament's efforts to preserve the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Sharif was referring to Leghari's refusal to sign the amendment
to the contempt of court Law.
</P>
<P>
He said that the steps taken by the president in recent days
have revealed the real cause of the "hysterical situation
prevailing in the country."
</P>
<P>
The prime minister noted that his government passed an
amendment to the contempt of court law to steer Pakistan out of
further crisis but President Leghari did not sign the bill.
</P>
<P>
The two houses of Parliament passed the bill on November 18.
The bill was forwarded to the president on the same day for his
assent. Under the Constitution, the president has a maximum of 30
days to sign it.  
</P>
