<HEADLINE> People Should Learn from Mao Zedong's Reading Habit: Li Ruihuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Li Ruihuan, a member of the
Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Chinese
Communist Party Central Committee, told members of a forum on the
book "Twenty Four Histories with Mao Zedong's Comments" here today
that the Chinese people should learn from the late Chairman's
reading habit.
</P>
<P>
He said that Mao's habit of reading history books and learning
from the past should be continued, and that the Chinese should
read more books in a diligent way.
</P>
<P>
The book is perhaps the most famous history book in China. It
is a record of Chinese history going back 5,000 years, written by
many authors in different dynasties.
</P>
<P>
The book was a favorite of many emperors and Mao himself liked
it very much and read it during wartime and during periods of
illness. He wrote notes and comments on almost every page his copy.
</P>
<P>
Li said that Mao's great historical deeds are not only the
result of his understanding of China and analysis of Chinese
society, but also of his study of Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
Mao was good at summing up historical experience and using
history as a mirror, Li said, and using all this, Mao created a
new history. Mao was a man who combined historical knowledge with
reality, and solved various modern problems, Li said. He then
recalled Deng Xiaoping's remarks about "opening up the future by
summarizing history" and President Jiang Zemin's statement that
"the whole Party should study history".
</P>
<P>
"In re-examing Mao's practice, we feel again the great charm and
vigor of Chinese civilization, which inspires us to continue the
fine traditional culture and build a socialist culture with
Chinese characteristics," Li concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
