<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Step Up Prevention Against Aids: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A senior European Union
official today said that prevention is still the only real way to
fight against aids.
</P>
<P>
Padraig Flynn, European commissioner in charge of employment
and social affairs including public health, said on this World
Aids Day, "No effort should be spared in the fight against this
scourge and prevention is still the only real way of acting on the
international front."
</P>
<P>
Treatment is bringing real improvement in Europe and in the
industrialized countries but it would be a mistake not to keep up
the effort with regard to behavioral patterns and prevention, said
the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
The European Union currently has some 500,000 HIV-infected
people and over 180,000 cases of full-blown aids disease have been
reported since the onset of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Three-quarters of the European cases were reported by Spain,
France and Italy.
</P>
<P>
According to recent reports published by the European
Commission, the UNAIDS and the World Bank, there are at least 30
million people in the world who are infected with the Human
Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV).
</P>
<P>
Over 90 percent of these people live in the developing
countries with two thirds of these people in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
