<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, December 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL -- Talks between South Korea and the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) on the terms of an IMF rescue package were
stalled on differences over the economic growth rate and the fate
of troubled financial institutions in the Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's Ministry of Finance and Economy announced early
today that the ministry and the visiting IMF delegation have
reached a provisional agreement on terms for an emergency bailout
package.
</P>
<P>
Finance and Economy Minister Lim Chang-yuel and IMF Managing
Director Michel Camdessus, however, were not successful in
negotiating the detailed terms of the bailout loan over the phone
later today.
</P>
<P>
In Manila, the Asian Development Bank (ADB) said today it will
provide a quick-disbursing emergency loan of up to 4 billion
U.S. dollars for South Korea's economic stabilization program and
structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- More than 10 Cambodian politicians, who have been
exiled since last July, today returned to the country from Thai
capital of Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The politicians, who were greeted at the airport by Lakhan
Mehotra, special envoy of United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, were all members of the Union of Cambodian Democrats, which
is made up of the PUNCINPEC, Khmer Buddhist Liberal Democratic
Party, Khmer Nation Party and Khmer Neutral Party.
</P>
<P>
Their purpose of coming back was to pave the way for ousted
Prince Norodom Ranariddh and some other exiled politicians to
return to the country safely and participate in the next year's
national election, they said.
</P>
<P>
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen ousted his rival Ranariddh, then
first prime minister, on July 6 after a weekend of fighting
between troops loyal to the two men. Ranariddh has been exiled
since then.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- A special meeting of the Federal Cabinet chaired
by Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif was held today to discuss the
prevailing constitutional crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
Official sources here said that the meeting continued for about
three hours. However, no further details were immediately
available.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chief of the Army Staff General Jehangir Karamat
today spent two hours with President Farooq Leghari at the
Presidential House and discussed with him the present
constitutional crisis.
</P>
<P>
The sources did not disclose any details of the meeting.
However, the source confirmed that the Chief of the Army Staff was
with the President for two hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
