<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Cut Funds in Some Regions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) may
cut its funds in some regions after 1999 but the cut has nothing
to do with its envisaged enlargement toward eastern and central
Europe, an EU spokeswoman said today.
</P>
<P>
The cut was only due to the fact that these regions have passed
the 75-percent EU funding threshold and "has nothing to do with
enlargement," the spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
Under the latest available figures published by the Eurostat,
regions qualifying for the objective one status, the highest
category for assistance from EU structural funds, must have
per-capita gross domestic product (GDP) at 75 percent of the EU
average or less, she said.
</P>
<P>
The regions to lose their objective one status may include
Lisbon in Portugal, Valencia in Spain, Corsica and Valenciennois
in France, Sardinia and Puglia in Italy, Hainaut in Belgium,
Flevoland in the Netherlands and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The future of EU regional aid is causing intense concern across
EU member states. The European Commission announced outline plans
as part of its Agenda 2000 budget proposals last July, but so far
regions are still not sure what their fate will be.
</P>
<P>
The European Council of Ministers is expected to make a
decision later next year after the statistics on which the
structural funds for 2000-2006 are to be based will be finalized.
</P>
<P>
Under Agenda 2000, the commission proposes to maintain
structural spending at 0.46 percent of the EU's GDP, or 275
billion ECUs (305 billion U.S. dollars) between 2000 and 2006.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
