<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Housing Remains Top Concern of HK People: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Housing-related problems
continued to top the list of most often mentioned issues affecting
Hong Kong people, according to a bimonthly survey conducted by the
Home Affairs Bureau (HAB).
</P>
<P>
Conducted between November 10 and 14, the survey found that 62
percent of the 1,526 respondents considered housing-related
problems their biggest concern, down one percentage point from
the September survey.
</P>
<P>
The number of people who felt that the government had handled
the problem well remained relatively unchanged at 14 percent,
while 68 percent considered that the government had exerted effort
in solving this top concern.
</P>
<P>
Economy-related problems were the second major concern of the
respondents, being mentioned by 29 percent of them, up from 12
percent in the last survey.
</P>
<P>
Among this group of people, 32 percent were worried about
inflation and the high cost of living, while another 25 percent
said fluctuations in the stock markets had affected them.
</P>
<P>
An HAB spokesman said that this could partly be explained by
the sharp fluctuations in the stock market in the last two weeks
of October.
</P>
<P>
However, the unease that some people felt was quickly mitigated
by the government's steadfast position to protect the Hong Kong
dollar, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that confidence in the local economy was
substantially restored by the international community's positive
assessment of the local government's handling of the difficulties
affecting the stock market and banking sector.
</P>
<P>
The survey, seventy-third in the series, also revealed that
Hong Kong's future as a problem was mentioned only by 5 percent of
the respondents.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 64 percent of people expected the existing situation
to improve or remain unchanged in the coming 12 months. 70 percent
said they were satisfied with the present situation and 72 percent
said they were confident that Hong Kong would continue to be
prosperous and stable.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
