<HEADLINE> HK Official Welcomes Heritage Foundation's Announcement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Administrative Secretary
Anson Chan today welcomed the announcement of the Heritage
Foundation which ranked Hong Kong the freest economy of the world
for the fourth year in a row.
</P>
<P>
"I very much welcome the announcement...There is even more to
savor in this accolade for us, as it comes so soon after the
establishment of Hong Kong as a Special Administrative Region
(SAR) of the People's Republic of China," she said.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1998 Index of Economic Freedom published here
earlier today by the foundation, Hong Kong's return to China has
done nothing to alter its status as the world's most open setting
in which to pursue economic activity.
</P>
<P>
The study "reminds us all once again about the fundamentals of
our economic faith," Chan said.
</P>
<P>
Above all, it recognizes that Hong Kong's economic structure
remains unchanged after the handover, as has been promised in the
Sino-British Joint Declaration and promulgated in the Basic Law,
she noted.
</P>
<P>
The head of 180,000-strong Hong Kong civil service expressed
her confidence in the local economy, as well as the Asian economy
as a whole, despite events in the past several months.
</P>
<P>
Chan pointed out that "there were a number of critical points"
that arose from the SAR government's recent experience in dealing
with stock and currency market fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
"Firstly, we demonstrate beyond doubt our political will to
defend the HK/U.S. dollar link," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Secondly, we showed that we have the mechanism and resources
to mount that defense, and sophisticated, effective and determined
officials to execute it," and thirdly, the community has faith in
the peg, she noted.
</P>
<P>
"Fourthly, and perhaps most significantly, the leadership in
Beijing has demonstrated in the most powerful and public way that
they respect Hong Kong's autonomy in running its own affairs,"
Chan pointed out.
</P>
<P>
She added that the moderate adjustments to the property and
equity markets following speculators' attack on the Hong Kong
dollar will make Hong Kong economy even more competitive.
</P>
</TEXT>
