<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU-Russia Partnership Agreement Hailed As Historic Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
hailed its Partnership and Cooperation Agreement with Russia,
which went into effect today, as a historic event.
</P>
<P>
The event marks a qualitatively new stage in relations between
the union and Russia, said a statement issued by Luxembourg, which
is serving as the six-month rotating presidency of the 15-nation
union.
</P>
<P>
With the agreement, which will be renewable annually after 10
years, the union is establishing with Russia a mutually beneficial
partnership of trust that will help consolidate the process of
democratic and economic reforms, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also marks the integration of Russia into the
European family and constitutes an instrument through which the union
and Russia can together consolidate peace, stability and security on
the European continent.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed in June 1994, covers various aspects
between the two sides including trade, science and technology and
education.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Russia will grant most-favored-nation status
to EU companies established in the country and the MFN status will
help loosen quantitative restrictions on imports from the EU and
ensure easier access to Russia's service market.
</P>
<P>
Hans van den Broek, EU commissioner responsible for external
relations with central and eastern Europe, said the agreement is a
positive affirmation of the evolving relationship between the EU
and Russia and reflects the growing importance the union attaches
to improving and deepening partnership and cooperation with the
country.
</P>
<P>
The EU considers Russia as one of its important trading
partners. In 1996, 40 percent of Russian exports, worth 22 billion
ECUs (26 billion U.S. dollars), went to the EU; 38 percent of EU's
exports, worth 19 billion ECUs (23 billion dollars), went to
Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
