<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rewi Alley's Gung Ho Movement Still Alive In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Rewi Alley Memorial
Co-operative Foundation held a ceremony here today for the 100th
anniversary of the birth of the New Zealand social activist, Rewi
Alley, tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Rewi Alley came to China in 1927 and lived in Beijing until his
death in 1987. Along with other foreigners and patriotic Chinese,
he started the Gung Ho Movement in Shanghai in 1937, at the
beginning of the Chinese People's War of Resistance against
Japanese Aggression.
</P>
<P>
He later served as general-manager of the Association of
Chinese Industrial Co-operatives, set up in Wuhan in 1938. The
more than 3,000 co-operatives across China provided much-needed
uniforms, blankets, arms, and ammunition for soldiers at the front.
</P>
<P>
At Alley's suggestion, the Association of Chinese Industrial
Co-operatives resumed activities in 1983, after some 30 years of
inactivity, and established more than 200 industrial co-operatives
promoting the growth of the socialist economy of China.
</P>
<P>
Yang Bo, president of the Rewi Alley Foundation, said at the
ceremony that the event is held to award outstanding co-operatives
and individuals to promote further development of the Gung Ho
Movement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
