<HEADLINE> Sudanese Refugees Enter N. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Some 200 Sudanese refugees
have crossed the border and entered northern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the refugees belong to Latugu tribe, and most
of them are women, children and old people, "The monitor"
reported today.
</P>
<P>
They were settled in Achopli and Kiryandongo refugees camps in
Kitgan district, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
The refugees said they left their homes in south Sudan to
avoid a conflicts between the Sudan People's Liberation Army
(SPLA) and the government troops.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA took up arms in 1983 to fight for self-determination
in the Christian south. Recent talks between the two sides in
Nairobi, Kenya failed to produce results as the SPLA insisted on
having a confederation with the Islamic north, rejecting
Khartoum's offer for federation.
</P>
<P>
A famine has occurred in southern Sudan right now and this has
weakened the fighting capacity of the SPLA, they held. 
</P>
