<HEADLINE> Silk Road Seminar Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUANZHOU, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from a dozen
countries and regions met today in Quanzhou, Fujian Province, for
a seminar on "China and Southeast Asia".
</P>
<P>
The three-day seminar is being held for the 10th anniversary of
a UNESCO study on the Silk Road, a photo exhibition, and
tree-planting event.
</P>
<P>
The 'Integral Study of the Silk Road', begun by UNESCO in 1988,
includes desert, maritime, grassland, and Buddhist studies, and
China has been active in the Silk Road Expedition and research for
the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Doudou Diene, a representative of the director-general of
UNESCO, told the gathering that it is worth mentioning that
Quanzhou, where the seminar is being held, is the only city in the
world to hold international seminars for UNESCO three time in the
last decade.
</P>
<P>
The Silk Roads Maritime Route Expedition made it clear that the
relations between China and Southeast Asia were rich in human,
spiritual, cultural and commercial ways, and that it is possible
to see what has been inherited from interaction over land routes,
from as far away as Central and North Asia.
</P>
<P>
Fujian's Vice-Governor Pan Xincheng said that research on the
Maritime Silk Road in Fujian has resulted in cultural and academic
exchanges with other countries and accelerated the pace of reforms
and ideological and ethical progress.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Xiaoyu, deputy secretary-general of the Chinese National
Commission for UNESCO, said that the Chinese government has always
placed great importance to co-operation with UNESCO and will
continue its participation in UNESCO activities and its support
for co-operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
