<HEADLINE> US's Northwest Airlines Helps Chinese Youngsters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Northwest Airlines of the
United States recently helped three Chinese children who were
suffering from heart disease, whose parents could not afford an
operation, by providing them and their parents with free tickets
to go for treatment in the US, according to the airline's Beijing
representative.
</P>
<P>
The parents of the three children, from Jiangxi and Hainan
provinces, and Beijing, came to Northwest seeking help after they
had heard about assistance the airline has given in the past.
</P>
<P>
Nine Chinese children have received similar assistance from the
airline. In August, the local media told the story of Wan
Zhaojiang, a two year-old who had just returned from a
Northwest-sponsored trip. Wan's given name of Zhaojiang was
changed to Xibei (or 'Northwest' in Chinese)" after the child was
operated on in the US.
</P>
<P>
Northwest started its Asian flights in 1947. To celebrate the
50th anniversary of its services in Asia, the airlines became
involved in a number of charitable activities in China, which
included a Children's art show, a 55,000-yuan donation to help
girls who had dropped out of primary schools in the Ningxia Hui
Autonomous Region, and free tickets to help eight universities and
hospitals in Beijing and Shanghai send 16 researchers to the
United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
