<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Outpaces Japan, U.S. in Industrial Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- For the fourth consecutive
month the European Union (EU) has outperformed Japan and the
United States in industrial growth, the Eurostat said in a report
released today.
</P>
<P>
During the three months from June to August this year, the
industrial production in the 15-nation union increased by 1.2
percent. Comparable rates in Japan and the United States were 0.8
percent and 1.1 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, the EU, Japan and the United States all
registered a growth rate of 1.3 percent, the Luxembourg-based
statistical agency said in the report.
</P>
<P>
While Japan and the United States experienced a drop the
following months, the union retained constant growth. The EU
increased 0.1 percentage point in May.
</P>
<P>
Finland scored the highest growth among EU member states that
posted above-average increases. It had a growth rate of 2.7
percent. Spain scored a 2.2-percent growth while Luxembourg and
Sweden were both up by 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Denmark was also above the average growth rate with a
1.5-percent increase.
</P>
<P>
Countries registering lower-than-average growth rates were
Britain with 0.9 percent, Germany with 0.8 percent, the
Netherlands with 0.5 percent, and Greece with 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The EU's industrial production growth is attributed by Eurostat
to an economic recovery that is being led by the capital and
intermediate goods sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
