<HEADLINE> Economy Books Tap Hong Kong's Success Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A set of seven books on Hong
Kong's economic policy was published here today, with an aim to
tell what is behind Hong Kong's success story and what can be
done for its continued success.
</P>
<P>
The seven books, as part of the 30-volume Hong Kong Economic
Policy Studies Series, were launched here today at a seminar
titled "Rethinking Economic Policies of Hong Kong", where authors
summed up their research findings.
</P>
<P>
The books focus on a variety of topical economic issues,
covering tourism, telecommunications, health care, labor, town
planning, housing, and water.
</P>
<P>
At today's seminar, the authors suggested that the Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government take a hands-off approach
to the economy, and let the market make decisions. They shared the
view that Hong Kong weathered the recent currency turmoil
sweeping Southeast Asia and Northeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's economic fundamentals are good though we are in a
business cycle of down string after so many years of rapid
growth," said Professor Richard Wong, director of the Hong Kong
Center for Economic Research.
</P>
<P>
He said that the sharp fall on stock and property markets was
not the end of Hong Kong. "Good trend will not eliminate
frustrations," Wong was upbeat about Hong Kong's future.
</P>
<P>
The economic research center coordinates the research projects
and writing of the series of books. The first batch of seven books
came to the shelves of book stores in April, and more will be put
out next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
