<HEADLINE> Typhoons in Western North Pacific to Take Asian Names from 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- From the year 2000 on,
typhoons in the western North Pacific will adopt Asian names, a
leading official of the Hong Kong Observatory announced here on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Typhoon Committee of the Economic and Social Commission for
Asia and the Pacific/World Meteorological Organization,
established in 1968, decided at its week-long 30th Session closing
here on Sunday to end the current use of American names, Lam Hing
Kwan, director of the Hong Kong Observatory and new chairman of
the Committee, said here today.
</P>
<P>
A special working group has been assigned the task of looking
into the details of implementation of the decision. The new naming
system is expected to put into operation in the year 2000, he said
at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
Currently, press and electronic media in some places in the
region use names given by the Guam-based U.S. military Joint
Typhoon Warning Center.
</P>
<P>
And for many years, the Typhoon Committee has been using a
numbering system to label the typhoons. The Committee, with
members from almost all the places affected by typhoons, thought
that a regionally agreed naming system should be set up for use in
the region.
</P>
<P>
As typhoons refer to tropical cyclones affecting many places in
East Asia, the committee members believed that the use of Asian
names would enhance the alertness of the people to approaching
typhoons, thus making warnings more effective, Lam said.
</P>
<P>
The committee members pledged to step up their cooperative
efforts to monitor atmospheric and hydrological conditions in the
region and to exchange speedily information among themselves, so
as to be in a better position to advise their respective
governments about the regional impacts of El Nino and any other
phenomena of similar time and space scales in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
