<HEADLINE> More Chinese Are Becoming Aware of AIDS Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The fact that several hundred
people in Beijing volunteered to have HIV/AIDS tests this year
shows a rise in the residents' awareness of the deadly disease,
according to Prof. Hu Xianghu of the Beijing Municipal Institute
of STD and AIDS (Sexually-Transmitted Diseases and Acquired Immuno
Deficiency Syndrome).
</P>
<P>
Through November of this year, the municipality found 35
HIV/AIDS cases, 18 of which were contracted by local residents,
raising the number of local HIV/AIDS patients to 55, Prof. Hu
said, and indicating a growing threat among local people.
</P>
<P>
Hu suggests that awareness of the means of transmission,
including contact with tainted blood, sexual contact, and parental
transmission, should be increased among the public.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a publicity and awareness campaign on HIV/AIDS
prevention is being carried out in Yunnan province in the
Southwest China, where 56 percent of the country's cases have been
reported.
</P>
<P>
A healthy life-style, mainly avoiding the use of drugs, is
being promoted among rural people and the young, because 91
percent of the HIV/AIDS cases were caused by contaminated
needles.
</P>
<P>
By the end of September, 4,678 HIV/AIDS cases have been
reported in the province, 55 percent of them in rural areas, and
46 percent among ethnic minorities.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry has had an education project in some ethnic
villages since 1991, with the help of the Yunnan Provincial
government. More than 80 percent of the people living in the
target areas have learned the basics of AIDS awareness, compared
with fewer than 20 percent previously.
</P>
<P>
Training courses on HIV/AIDS prevention have been held in 26
areas on the Vietnam, Laos and Myanmar borders, where AIDS is
prevalent.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, teachers at primary and middle schools have also been
involved in health education programs to guarantee a safer life
for their students, and to keep them from contracting AIDS, local
health officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
