<HEADLINE> AIDS Spiraling in S. Africa's Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The prevalence of
AIDS/HIV in South Africa's armed forces is increasing by eight
percent every year, The Star newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Researchers speaking at the recent launch of the Southern
African Civil Military Alliance, part of a worldwide network,
said it was plausible that, given the spread of the disease, up
to eight percent of South African National Defense Force
personnel are infected every year.
</P>
<P>
No overall figure for the incidence of the disease in the
military has been disclosed, but one regiment has been blamed for
the spread of HIV to remote communities in Kwazulu-Natal and the
Northern Cape provinces.
</P>
<P>
It is known that the military has higher sexually transmitted
infection rates than the general population.
</P>
<P>
Researchers said the AIDS/HIV epidemic in southern African is
more serious than in central Africa.
</P>
<P>
While data was difficult to obtain from military forces, it
had been established that in Zimbabwe, 50 percent of soldiers
were HIV infected, in the Central African Republic, 22 percent of
recruits were HIV positive, and in Congo, a total of 63 percent
of Deaths of soldiers in its armed forces were caused by AIDS or
HIV infection, rather than through bullet wounds or other causes.
</P>
</TEXT>
