<HEADLINE> Chinese Health Officials Say Children Need HIV Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Health officials and HIV/AIDS
control experts say that early prevention of HIV infections in
Chinese children is needed, even if there are few infections now.
</P>
<P>
About 10 percent of the 8,277 cases of HIV infections reported
in China by the end of September were in people below the age of
18, according to Health Minister Chen Minzhang, who said that most
of the cases were the result of drug use, usually in sharing
contaminated needles.
</P>
<P>
"Children in our country also face the dreary situation of HIV
infections," Chen said, pointing out that drug use is the result
of "ignorance and curiosity".
</P>
<P>
Illegal activities that some young people may get involved in
make them vulnerable to HIV infection by sexual transmission,
Chen said today at a meeting for World AIDS Day.
</P>
<P>
"We should give adolescents enough knowledge about AIDS
prevention as early as possible through community, school, and
family efforts," he said.
</P>
<P>
Health Ministry officials say they are planning to join family
planning and women's health departments to provide more
information.
</P>
<P>
One State Education Commission official said that information
about HIV/AIDS and sexually transmitted diseases (STDs) has become
part of a compulsory health education program for middle school
and college students.
</P>
<P>
"We've asked middle schools to make students aware of sex,
HIV/AIDS, and STDs. Universities and colleges are also required to
improve sex ethics education," Zhang Xin, who is in charge of
hygiene and health education, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the colleges and universities are doing this job, and
we plan to conduct the same activities in middle schools gradually,"
she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
