<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Activists Mark World AIDS Day With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Israeli activists
marked the World AIDS day here today with a demonstration to
protest the Treasury's refusal to cover the costs of the drug that
slows the progress of the HIV virus.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Israel Coalition of AIDS (Acquired Immune
Deficiency Syndrome) Organization, the activists gathered at the
front gate of parliament, to urge the inclusion of the AIDS
medication in health basket.
</P>
<P>
If the Treasury allocates 12.8 million U.S. dollars a year in
this field, only the cost of a F-15 jet's wing, all AIDS patients
in the country would get the medications, including the drug
"cocktail" that slows the progress of the HIV (Human
Immuno-Deficiency Virus), one of the organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Yehoshua Metza told the parliament session
today that the costs of AIDS drug should be included in the basket
of health services.
</P>
<P>
Although the drug "cocktail" is expensive, he said,
hospitalizing AIDS patients without giving them the "cocktail" is
even more costly.
</P>
<P>
The "cocktail" and other anti-AIDS drugs have reportedly cut
the mortality rate from the fatal disease by 20 percent in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Yaakov Neeman has said he will include the
AIDS "cocktail" in the basket of health services provided that
other medications are removed from it.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry spends about 2.4 million U.S. dollars a
year in fighting AIDS. This sum of money was spent on information
campaigns and blood testing but not on hospitalization of
patients and the operation of an AIDS hospice.
</P>
<P>
A survey, conducted shortly before this year's World AIDS day
by Israel representative of condom manufacturer Durex, found that
85 percent of Israelis who have sex with new partners do not use
condom.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest Health Ministry statistics, a total of
467 Israelis have contracted full-fledged AIDS since 1981, and
only 89 of them are still alive.
</P>
<P>
There also have been 1,646 HIV carriers. But actual numbers are
estimated to be twice of that or more, Health Ministry
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
