<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Meteorology Satellite Begins Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A Fengyun-2 (FY-2)
geostationary meteorology satellite officially went into operation
for the China Meteorology Satellite Center today, after 160 days
of trial operation.
</P>
<P>
Song Jian, state councillor and minister in charge of the State
Science and Technology Commission, said at a ceremony that the
FY-2 is a product of Chinese high technolgy, and that the
successful design proves that China can develop its own high
technology by itself.
</P>
<P>
He said that the satellite will play an important role in
China's meteorology services and will have significant social and
economic benefits.
</P>
<P>
He urged continued supports for meteorology satellite services
and for their use in the economy and national defense.
</P>
<P>
The satellite was sent up on June 10 and was in position on
June 17 and has sent 3,000 photos.
</P>
<P>
A State Meteorology Administration official says that the FY-2
will provide good information about weather changes in China and
in neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will also contribute to international
co-operation and to disaster forecasts in the Asia-Pacific
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
