<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sub-Saharan Africa Suffers Most From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Sub-Saharan Africa is the
region with the fastest-moving AIDS epidemic and already home of
two-thirds of HIV carriers in the world, according to a U.N.
report available here today, the World AIDS Day.
</P>
<P>
People infected with HIV now make up 7.4 percent of all those
aged between 15 and 49 in the region, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Unprotected sex between men and women accounted for most of
the 3.4 million new HIV infections estimated among adults in
sub-Saharan Africa this year. This accounted for 58.6 percent of
the new HIV infections all over the world this year.
</P>
<P>
High fertility combined with poor access to information and
services for the prevention of mother-to-child transmission
resulted in some 530,000 infected children being born to mothers
with HIV in the region, making up some 90 percent in the world.
</P>
<P>
In general, western Africa sees its rates of infection
stabilize at much lower levels than in eastern and southern
Africa while southern Africa continues to be part of the
continent worst hit by the fatal disease, said the report.
</P>
<P>
By early 1997, the South African government estimated that 2.4
million people in the country were living with HIV, up by more
than one third over 1996.
</P>
<P>
In Botswana, the proportion of the adult population infected
with HIV has doubled over the last five years. Up to 43 percent
of pregnant women tested in the major urban center of Francistown
were HIV-positive in 1997.
</P>
<P>
HIV infection was estimated at one in five adults in Zimbabwe
in 1996. In capital Harare, 32 percent of pregnant women were
already infected with the virus in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In Beitbridge, another major city in Zimbabwe, the proportion
shot up from 32 percent in 1995 to 59 percent last year. Although
levels in cities were slightly higher than in rural areas, the
difference was not great, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
The disease has already killed 230,000 Kenyans while about 1.3
million are said to be HIV positive in the country. It is
expected that about one million Kenyans may die of AIDS by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Official data also indicated that as many as 2.2 million
people are currently living with HIV in Nigeria, a country whose
response to the epidemic needs strengthening, the report said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 5.8 million people were newly infected with HIV
this year, adding the number of HIV-carriers in the world to more
than 30 million, including 1.1 million children under age 15.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that an estimated 2.3 million people died of
AIDS in 1997, representing a fifth of the total 11.7 million
deaths since the disease was first discovered in the early 1980s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
