<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 PKK Rebels Killed in Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Iraq's Kurdistan Democratic
Party (KDP) killed seven rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK) coming from Iran, the semi-official Anatolia News
Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that KDP forces surrounded a group of about 200
PKK militants Saturday, who infiltrated from Iran and are trying
to shelter themselves between Pirbela and Snath camps in northern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The KDP exchanged heavy fires with the PKK guerrillas near
Snath camp in the region at Sunday noon and shot dead seven PKK
rebels in the clash, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
It added that it is difficult for the PKK rebels to enter into
Turkey due to the strict security measures taken by the Turkish
government troops so that some PKK militants have tried to shelter
themselves in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The KDP and the Turkish security forces support each other in
fighting against the PKK and KDP's rival Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK) in northern Iraq. Turkey often launches
cross-border attacks on PKK in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
So far, there are about 2,500 or 3,000 PKK rebels still
staying in northern Iraq and they often infiltrate into Turkey to
attack Turkish military and civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a 13-year-old separatist war for
autonomy in eastern and southeastern Turkey, which has claimed
over 28,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
