<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Shilling Tumbles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 1 (Xinhua) -- After days of steady
decline, the Tanzanian Shilling ended lower last week and does
not appear to have found a floor, according to the Daily News
today.
</P>
<P>
"We are short of Dollars, very short, so we are seeing the
Shilling depreciating," a senior treasury official at a leading
foreign bank said.
</P>
<P>
The Shillings had depreciated to 630 to the Dollar by the end
of last week.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Tanzania (BOT) said the Shilling was
trading at a mid-rate of 617.8194 Friday compared to last
613.8396 on the previous Friday.
</P>
<P>
Some market participants said the Shilling would get a boost
this month if the International Monetary Fund (IMF) grants
Tanzania the extra credit it had requested to offset the effects
of drought.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has asked for additional special drawing rights,
worth about 28 million U.S. Dollars under the IMF's enhanced
structural adjustment facility (Esaf).
</P>
<P>
If that credit is approved when the IMF board meets next
month, it will give "an upward push to the supply of Dollars in
the market, analysts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
