<HEADLINE> France Expels D.R. Congo Diplomat in Retaliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- France today expelled a first
secretary of the embassy of the Democratic Republic of Congo
(D.R. Congo) in Paris, in retaliation of the expulsion by the
D.R. Congo of a first secretary of the French embassy in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry today summoned the charge
d'affaires of the D.R. Congo, Tadumi On'Okoko, ordering the
departure of the first secretary Yeye Lobota to leave France
before the end of the week, said a foreign ministry spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the decision to declare Lobota persona
non grata was based on the Vienna Convention authorizing a country
to declare a foreign diplomat persona non grata.
</P>
<P>
The D.R. Congo authorities expelled the first secretary of the
French embassy Eric Lubin for "activities incompatible with his
status." 
