<HEADLINE> World Labor Congress to Discuss Globalization Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Confederation of
Labor (WCL) began its 24th congress here today to deliberate how
people can benefit from globalization and how the WCL can help
them.
</P>
<P>
The six-day congress, under the theme "from
internationalization to globalization: struggle to change course,"
is expected to discuss the wide-ranging social consequences, both
positive and negative, of the globalization process.
</P>
<P>
The WCL believes that while the globalization process has its
positive side, such as promoting contacts, business and
cooperation, it also has a lot of negative consequences, such as
growing inequalities between people, sectors and countries, and
widening gap between the poor and the rich.
</P>
<P>
What is more, economy is escaping more and more the national
laws, paving the way for "a wild, unbridled and arrogant
liberalism."
</P>
<P>
WCL President Willy Peirens said in a statement that
globalization is dictated too much by financial or economic
groups, which want to make profits, and even want to make profits
without having to pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from about 112 countries and regions are
participating in the congress.  
</P>
</TEXT>
