<HEADLINE> World Oil Prices Will Not Drop, Expert Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- World oil prices will not
plunge even though the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC) raised production ceiling to 27.5 million barrels
per day (bpd) from 25.033 million bpd, former OPEC secretary
general Soebroto said here today.
</P>
<P>
"I do not think that the price of oil will drop," he said after
a meeting between President Soeharto and delegates from OPEC
member countries who were attending the organization's 103rd
ministerial meeting here.
</P>
<P>
The six-day meeting, which concluded today, made the decision
on the production ceiling after a tough debate among the member
countries. Some members proposed to increase the quota on an
estimation that world oil demand next year will increase by 1.8 to
1.9 million bpd. But some others worried about the drop of oil
price following the increase of production.
</P>
<P>
The new quota will be effective from January 1, 1998, and is
still below the 28 million bpd of production during October 1997,
he said.
</P>
<P>
In October, the price of oil ranged from 18 to 20 U.S. dollars
a barrel.
</P>
<P>
"If oil prices drop, OPEC will hold a special meeting and
discuss its oil production," Soebroto noted.
</P>
<P>
OPEC wants to be the leader in the oil market, he said.
</P>
<P>
Soebroto said that oil producing countries are still trying to
develop the technology for new oil products which would be
friendlier to the environment.
</P>
<P>
Oil and energy ministers from OPEC's 11 member countries --
Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Libya, Nigeria, Qatar,
Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates and Venezuela -- attended
the meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
