<HEADLINE> Sea Port Blocked in Beef Imports Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 1 (Xinhua) -- About 600 Welsh farmers
blockading the Irish port of Holyhead today threw a truckload of
Irish beef-burgers into the sea.
</P>
<P>
The farmers have protested through the night at falling beef
prices, particularly of imports from the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
The British Broadcasting Corporation said that they prevented
trucks from entering the port and only allowed passengers and cars
through. However, no one was hurt and no arrests were made.
</P>
<P>
Most protesters finally left the port at around 5:30 a.m.
following negotiations with ferry operators.
</P>
<P>
The farmers were reportedly seeking an urgent meeting with
Welsh Secretary Ron Davies to discuss the situation.
</P>
<P>
British beef farmers' incomes have plunged since the discovery
of link between bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) and its
brain-wasting human equivalent, Creutzfeldt Jakob disease (CJD).
</P>
