<HEADLINE> HK People Urged to register for Legislative Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Registration
and Electoral Office is accelerating its efforts to urge more
people to conduct voter registration for the first Legislative
Council election of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) next May.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters on the progress of the voter registration
here this afternoon, Justice Woo Kwok-hing, chairman of the
Electoral Affairs Commission, said the voter registration exercise
is in full swing.
</P>
<P>
He said that to make the election a success and earnestly
implement the principles of "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong"
and a high-degree of autonomy, the paramount task now is to sign
up as many electors as possible and to update the electoral roll.
</P>
<P>
"We are moving full steam ahead to compile three separate
provisional registers for public inspection in mid-February: one
for the five geographical constituencies, one for the 28
functional constituencies and the other for the subsectors," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Woo said that the Home Affairs Department of Hong Kong will
mobilize 30,000 voter registration ambassadors from December 6 to
12 to make door-to-door visits to every household across the SAR.
</P>
<P>
The department staff will visit major organizations later this
month to remind them to advise their members to register.
</P>
<P>
The deadline for the voter registration is set on January 16
next year.
</P>
<P>
The election of the first Legislative Council is seen as one of
the most important work of the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
The 60-member Legislative Council will be made up of 20 seats
to be returned from five geographical constituencies through
direct elections, 30 seats from 28 functional constituencies and 10
seats from the 800-member Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
The Election Committee is expected to be formed through
subsector election in early April 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
