<HEADLINE> Seoul Stock Prices Drop to Ten-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The composite share price index
in Seoul stock market today tumbled below the psychological
400-point level for the first time in 10 years, among concerns
about too harsh conditions stuch to the IMF bailout package for
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Share prices, dropping for the eighth consecutive day, fell
14.70 points to 393.16, the lowest since June 1987.
</P>
<P>
During the day's sluggish trading, panicky investors dumped
shares indiscriminately as news spread that the IMF had demanded a
swift restructuring and consolidation of banking institutions with
weak track records.
</P>
<P>
Investors, also fearing a back-to-back collapse of businesses,
continued to cut their losses and bail out, dealers said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, government officials said that Seoul and
the IMF have agreed on the terms of the bailout loan at 1 a.m.
today and the agreement is waiting for an approval in a cabinet
meeting slated for later today.
</P>
<P>
However, latest news reports said that the terms are not
finally decided and that Seoul may have to slash its economic
growth ratio to as low as 2.5 percent to meet the IMF's demands.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Lim Chang-yuel notified the IMF
delegation today that they start anew the negotiations on several
differences for the rescue funds.
</P>
<P>
Financial analysts noted that the worst in Seoul stock market
was yet to come, as the restructuring process following the IMF
loan would be launched in earnest next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
