<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 20M Nigerians Prone to Iodine Deficiency Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- No fewer than 20 million
Nigerians are prone to iodine deficiency disease, an expert said
at a national seminar over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The disease is mostly associated with cassava growing areas
where people get their source of drinking water from the wells,
said Beatrice Irobo, Delta state coordinator of the iron
deficiency anaemia control program.
</P>
<P>
"The number of people at the risk of the iodine deficiency
disease forms about 20 percent of the entire population who are
already anaemic," she said, quoted by the Punch newspaper today.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's population is estimated at around 100 million.
</P>
<P>
In order to mitigate the effects of the disease on too many
people, according to the expert, the federal government and
United Nations Children's Fund are trying to create enough
awareness in various states of the country, particularly at the
grass-root level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
