<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nagano Olympics Organisiers Agree to Raise Downhill Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Nagano Winter Olympics organisers
agreed to raise the starting point of the men's downhill course on
Monday, ending a four-year-long dispute shadowing the Games.
</P>
<P>
The compromising decision was expected to be finalized late in
the day by the major officials of the Nagano Olympic Organising
Committee (NAOC).
</P>
<P>
New downhill course was poised to stretch into the protected
national park.
</P>
<P>
The International Ski Federation (FIS) required to extend the
course to 1,800 meters from the original 1,680 meters, the
shortest in the Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
But the NAOC officials declined the requirement due to Japan's
environmental laws which ban any constructions in protected areas.
</P>
<P>
The new compromise plan, which was drawn by FIS downhill
designer Bernard Russi, claimed a start at 1,765 meters above sea
level, a stretch skirting ouside the reserve -- down a narrow
strip by the edge of the mountain dotted with towers for ski lifts.
</P>
<P>
NAOC's secretariat, dominated by local administrators, recently
agreed to raise the starting point. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Airways Unveils New Growth Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Airways will make major
changes in its routes and flights network in Europe, the Middle
East and West Africa to raise revenue which grew by 13.2 percent
between March and September, a local report said today.
</P>
<P>
Unaudited results for the first six months of the fiscal year
starting from March showed that the company's revenue rose to 5.7
billion Shillings (89 million U.S. Dollars) from five billion
Shillings (78 million Dollars) in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The national carrier would buy one new B737 aircraft and lease
two more. A fourth would be delivered in March 1999, bringing the
fleet of B737s to six, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The airline would axe its Rome and Paris flights and
discontinue the use of Fokker aircraft over the next three months
while trying to expand regional connections, Chief Executive
Brian Davies was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Rome and Paris routes were no longer viable because of
competition from cheaper chartered flights, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the airline will introduce two flights a week to
Douala, Cameroun and three to Lagos, Nigeria. Also planned are
additional flights to Cairo, Khartoum and Kigali, capitals of
Egypt, Sudan and Burundi respectively.
</P>
<P>
The company will also double flights to Dubai and increase the
number of connecting flights through Nairobi, said Davies.
</P>
<P>
"The target is to provide a maximum two-hour connecting time
between flights with improved passenger transfer and baggage
systems," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The airline today also launched a cooperation pact with Eagle
Aviation to expand a network of domestic services over the next
two years, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
