<HEADLINE> Southeast China Improving Port Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Southeast China's Fujian
Province expects to increase the number of deep-water berths to 50
from the present 31 and their total handling capacity to 69
million tons by the year 2000, Governor He Guoqiang told a recent
symposium on Fujian port development.
</P>
<P>
It expects to have 120 to 135 deep-water berths with a total
handling capacity of 180 to 200 million tons by 2010.
</P>
<P>
Fujian increased its ports' handling capacity from 3.9 million
tons in 1978 to 39 million tons in 1996, with Fuzhou and Xiamen as
the main ports, and making Fujian one of the top 10 port areas in
the country.
</P>
<P>
The governor said that for more than a decade, Fujian has spent
a large amount of money on port construction, improving them
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the province had 99 1,000-ton berths
and 31 10,000-ton berths.
</P>
<P>
Fujian should make ports the hub of its transport system, the
governor stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
