<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Using Japanese Loans to Control River Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan Province
will use 100 million US dollars in 30-year Japanese loan to deal
with the serious pollution of the province's largest Xiangjiang
River.
</P>
<P>
With a State Council approval, the province will begin water and
air pollution control projects along the river with the loans and
1.23 billion billion yuan (140 million US dollars) from China.
</P>
<P>
The Xiangjiang watershed covers 40 percent of Hunan's area and
about 60 percent of its population. Because large amounts of
industrial and household wastes are discharged into the river
daily and gas emissions cause acid rain, people's lives have
been threatened.
</P>
<P>
Hunan will build 24 pollution control projects along the river
in 1998: seven urban waste water treatment projects, six urban gas
and liquefied gas projects, three urban garbage treatment projects,
and eight industrial pollution control projects.
</P>
<P>
After the first-phase construction, pollution of the river is
expected to be reduced by more than 30 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
