<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Light but Frothy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
surged to its highest close in 14 trading days today as better
Asian markets prompted some bargain hunters to snap up cheapened
blue chip shares.
</P>
<P>
In a late surge, the all ordinaries broke through the 2500
barrier for the first time since November 13, closing 48.3 points,
or 1.96 percent, higher at 2513.4.
</P>
<P>
However, brokers said the improvement was exaggerated by the
thin volume of today's trade as many buyers chose to see further
evidence of a calming of Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
National turnover for the day was just 270.92 million shares at
a value of 521.22 million U.S. dollars, with rises outnumbering
falls 516 to 500.
</P>
<P>
Larger stocks were the main beneficiary of today's trade, with
shares such as BHP, WMC and ICI - all of which had notably
suffered over the past two months - increasing significantly.
</P>
<P>
"It was pretty thin trade but the Asian markets were pretty
firm," Steve Mayne from Nevitts said.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the resource stocks have bounced back after a real
selldown in recent times and there may have been some bargain
buying there and some readjustment," Mayne said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index rose 71.5 points to 4301.9.
</P>
<P>
ICI was the best performed of the major resource stocks,
jumping 52.5 cents to 10.54 dollars after a November plunge.
</P>
<P>
Among the major banks, Westpac was the most improved,
increasing 22.2 cents, National Australia Bank rose 35.3 cents,
ANZ lifted by 11 cents while Commonwealth was 6.9 cents better.
</P>
<P>
Resource stocks outstripped industrials today, and the all
resources index closed 30.9 points higher, or 2.92 percent, at
1087.6.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks were broadly better today as the bullion price
improved 8.00 U.S. dollars per ounce on Friday's close to 296.50.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
