<HEADLINE> Pak Apex Court Judges Adjourn Scheduled Hearings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The full-court and full-bench
hearings fixed for today separately have been adjourned at the
request of representatives of various bar associations.
</P>
<P>
The two separate hearings were called by Justice Saeed Uzzman
Siddiqui and Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah respectively.
</P>
<P>
The full-court meeting was scheduled to hear petitions against
the appointment of the chief justice while the full-bench meeting
was to hear petitions against Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif on the
alleged contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
All 17 judges of the apex court agreed to have informal
meetings to sort out the matters and not to hold the scheduled
hearings today, President of Supreme Court Bar Association Abid
Hasan Minto told the media this morning.
</P>
<P>
According to Minto, the judges agreed to adjourn the two
separate meetings of the benches, and held an informal meeting to
discuss the matters pending with the apex court.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Supreme Court said that the judges had an
informal get-together this morning to discuss the "two cause
lists" which were issued separately on Saturday and sort out other
related matters.
</P>
<P>
A 15-member delegation of the various bar associations this
morning persuaded the judges to sit together and resolve the issue
themselves.
</P>
<P>
Minto said they succeeded in their efforts and all the 17
judges sat together for more than one hour. They were scheduled to
meet again this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said the judges were discussing the issues of their common
concern.
</P>
<P>
By accepting their proposals the bench expressed solidarity
with the bars, hoping that the matter may be amicably resolved,
Minto added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tight security measures were observed outside the
Supreme Court building and no outsider without valid passes were
allowed to enter the court's premises.
</P>
<P>
On the directives of Interior Minister Chaudhry Shujat Hussain,
the local administration adopted strict measures to maintain law
and order on the occasion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
