<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Weaker After Quarterly Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar ended
weaker today, as worse than expected quarterly current account
data added to the list of woes already surrounding the local
currency.
</P>
<P>
The currency finished at 67.88 U.S. cents, down from 68.03
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics reported today that the
seasonally adjusted current account deficit widened to 4.63
billion Australian dollars (3.14 billion U.S. dollars) in the
September quarter, from 2.98 billion Australian dollars (2.02
billion U.S. dollars) in the June quarter. The outcome was worse
than market expectations of a deficit of 4.10 billion.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the current account was likely to get worse
going into 1998, due to the risk that Australian export volumes
and commodity prices would fall on the back of a slowdown in Asian
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
ANZ head of foreign exchange sales John Reedyk said, "With all
the turmoil in Asia there is going to be less demand for our
commodities and less demand for our exports than there has been
over the past few years."
</P>
<P>
Rothschild Australia treasury manager Paul Macarounas said the
data today only adds to the worries already surrounding the
currency such as falling commodity prices and an economic slowdown
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian dollar now looked like finding a base of
support around 67.70 U.S. cents, although a break of that level
would bring it down to 66.80," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar closed today at 86.69
Japanese yen, from 86.74 last Friday, and at 1.1980 German marks,
from 1.1981.  
</P>
</TEXT>
