<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Halve Armed Forces By 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 1 (Xinhua)-- South Africa is to
continue pruning its armed forces from a high of 135,000
personnel to around 70,000 by 1999, local daily, The Star
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Various voluntary retrenchment and rationalization processes
are now in operation, the newspaper quoted unidentified sources
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The number in the South African National Defense Force swelled
in 1994/95 as a result of the integration of the former South
African Defense Force, the military wing of the ruling African
National Congress, and about 2,000 members of the KwaZulu Natal
para-military force.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures indicate there remain only 90,000 uniformed
and civilian personnel. Thousands more will probably go during
1998 with the remainder in the first four months of 1999, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Contingency plans have been drawn up by the Department of
Defense to close a key naval base and two air-force bases in the
wake of further budget cut.
</P>
<P>
The proposed 1998-99 military budget is to be discussed by
defense and other government officials in Cape Town on December 3
prior to a final allocation being made known when the national
budget is presented.
</P>
<P>
The current financial year allocation for defense totaled
about 10 billion Rand (2.08 billion U.S. Dollars ), and this is
expected to cut by at least 500 million Rand (104 million U.S.
Dollars) after earlier expectations that funding would be
increased marginally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Chinese Official on Macao Civil Service Localization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official in
Macao said the localization of Macao's civil service must proceed
from reality and be conducted in accordance with the Basic Law,
and that the permanent residents of Portuguese origin should be
treated equally in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qiren, director of the Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch,
told Ryuichiro Nakamura, chief of the Hong Kong bureau of Japan's
NHK, in an interview last week that the Chinese side sticks to
three principles on the issue of the localization of Macao's civil
service.
</P>
<P>
Certain progress has been made over the past several years due
to the good cooperation between China and Portugal, and the joint
efforts of all sides, he said.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, more than 70 percent of the lower
ranking service was localized, and this year has seen progress in
the higher ranking positions, he noted, adding that the first
Chinese took the position of department chief last month.
</P>
<P>
But he stressed that what has been done so far is not enough.
</P>
<P>
"The progress is not satisfactory, considering the fact that
there are only a little more than two years left before the
handover of power (in 1999)," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang pointed out that to realize the localization of the civil
service as early as possible is required by the Basic Law, and
this is the first principle of the Chinese side.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law of Macao clearly states that the civil service
must be localized, and that main posts of the future Special
Administrative Region (SAR) should be held by Chinese citizens
from among Macao's permanent residents.
</P>
<P>
"The localization of middle and senior ranking officials should
be quickened through great efforts," he said. "That is demanded by
law in the interest of a smooth transition and smooth handover,
and everything should be done according to law."
</P>
<P>
The second principle is that the localization should start from
 the reality in Macao. Macao is a multiple society and Chinese
residents account for 97 percent of the population, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In a society like this, the will of the overwhelming Chinese
residents should be reflected in the future SAR administration,"
he said. "The proportion of Chinese citizens from among Macao's
permanent residents should be raised in the senior and middle rank
service so that the civil service of the future SAR will better
serve the broad residents."
</P>
<P>
The third principle, he said, is that the Macao-born Portuguese
permanent residents of Macao among the civil service are welcome
to stay on in the civil service of the future SAR.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the Chinese side has made very clear that all
people are equal before the law of the Macao SAR, and no
communities shall be treated unequally because they are
minorities.
</P>
<P>
"It is the wish of the Chinese side to maintain a stable force
of civil servants," he said. "The Macao-born Portuguese civil
servants are welcome to stay on as servants of the Macao SAR if
they wish to do so."
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, if relevant government departments of the
Macao SAR deem it necessary, they can employ Portuguese and other
foreign nationals as advisors or to fill professional and
technical posts.
</P>
<P>
Wang stressed that the three principles are required by the
resumption of exercise of China's sovereignty over Macao on
December 20, 1999. They also conform to the spirit of the
Sino-Portuguese Joint Declaration and the Macao basic law, and
serve the interests of both China and Portugal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 10:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Histadrut Strike Enters 2nd Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 1 (Xinhua)-- The strike by estimated
150,000 Israeli clerks and municipal workers entered its second
day today in defiance of a National Labor Court ruling Saturday
which permitted only a 24-hour walkout.
</P>
<P>
The Histadrut, also known as Israeli National Trade Union, the
organizer of the strike, held a meeting today to discuss widening
the strike by asking civil servants and bank workers to join in
the strike if progress can not be made in the talks with the
Treasury.
</P>
<P>
The strike encompassing workers of 360 local authorities
has paralyzed operations of day care centers, nursery schools,
government corporations and national institutions like the Jewish
Agency and Jewish National Fund.
</P>
<P>
Many schools were also disrupted, since maintenance personnel
and secretaries are also on strike.
</P>
<P>
An additional 20,000 clerks joined the strike today, which
affected hospitals, universities and colleges.
</P>
<P>
The strike was launched Sunday in protest against government
demands for cost-cutting measures by local authorities to reduce
an overall deficit of 11.4 billion U.S. dollars. Some cuts will
erase worker's bonuses, the Histadrut said.
</P>
<P>
Histadrut strike organizer Shlomo Shani and Treasury director
of wages Yossi Kucik met Saturday afternoon, but no progress was
made in resolving their differences.
</P>
<P>
The National Labor Court, which upheld the 24-hour strike, is
expected to decide today about whether to issue back-to-work
orders.
</P>
<P>
The worst effects of the strike are felt by parents,
especially single mothers, who could not send their children to
kindergartens since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, sanitation workers' strike entered its fifth day
today in Tel Aviv and the city's 106 emergency services were
closed down to support the sanitation workers' strike against the
city authority for contracting private companies for garbage
collections.
</P>
<P>
Police arrested 26 sanitation workers Saturday on suspicion
of sabotaging 22 garbage trucks belonging to private contractors.
</P>
<P>
The Tel Aviv sanitation workers still refuse to return to
work, despite court orders instructing them to do so.
</P>
<P>
This is the second largest nation-wide strike in Israel this
year. The previous one was organized by the Histadrut at the end
of September, which paralyzed all sectors of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 200 People Poisoned in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 200 people were
taken ill for suspected food poisoning after they ate sweetdish at
a dinner party in Rajkot city, about 1,262 kilometers southwest of
New Delhi, Sunday night, Press Trust of India (PTI) quoted police
as saying here today.
</P>
<P>
The victims started vomiting and suffered from diarrhea when
they returned home from the party. All the affected people, who
were admitted to hospital, were reported to have been out of
danger.
</P>
<P>
Samples of food, prepared by a local hotel, had been sent to a
laboratory for necessary test.  
</P>
</TEXT>
