<HEADLINE> India's Upper House Adjourned Indefinitely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 1 (Xinhua)-- India's Rajya Sabha (Upper
House of Parliament) was adjourned sine die here today following
the resignation of the United Front (UF) government on the evening
of November 28 after the Congress withdrew its support to the
government the same day.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the House R.C. Tripathi laid on the table
of the House the letter of resignation of Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral and the letter of President K.R. Narayanan requesting
him to continue in office till alternative arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Parliamentary Affairs Mrs. Jayanti
Natrajan asked the House to be adjourned sine die and Chairman of
the House and Vice President Krishan Kant also agreed.
</P>
<P>
Like the Lower House of Parliament, the Upper House could not
transact any business after it met for winter session on November
19 and it had to be adjourned daily after meeting for a few
minutes.
</P>
<P>
Normal functioning of the House was paralyzed with the Congress
MPs insisting in their demand for the removal of three ministers
of the Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam (DMK), one of the UF
constituents, from the Union government following the indictment
of the party in the interim report of the Jain Commission probing
the Rajiv Gandhi assassination case in 1991. The report was tabled
before the two Houses on November 20 by the government.
</P>
<P>
The Lok Sabha (Lower House of Parliament) was adjourned sine
die last Tuesday for the same reason but it is being reconvened
Tuesday. The decision to reconvene the Lower House was taken on
Friday before the Gujral government resigned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
