<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Says His Sweden Visit Beyond Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said that the main purpose of his visit to Sweden is to strengthen
coordination between the two countries "in solving key world and
European problems."
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the eve of his visit, Yeltsin said Russia will
manage to coordinate positions on many issues with Sweden.
</P>
<P>
He said the talks between the two sides will be devoted to
bilateral relations, above all, to economic cooperation. "A solid
package of agreements" will be signed during the visit, Yeltsin
said.
</P>
<P>
These agreements will include rescheduling former USSR debt
owed to Sweden, promoting cooperation in the safe use of nuclear
energy in peaceful purposes, in space exploration, and in culture,
science, and education, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Russia and Sweden have already achieved much in removing the
obstacles to their trade and economic ties," he said. "Work toward
settling the problem of the former USSR commercial debt to Swedish
firms is nearing completion."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin noted that Russian-Swedish trade turnover had doubled
over the last five years. But he emphasized that it is so far
"clearly inadequate" since "the powerful economic potential of our
countries allows them to interact far more actively."
</P>
<P>
The president expressed the hope that Sweden will put more
investment to Russia, saying that Swedish investments in Russia
have so far fallen short of Sweden's real potential.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the rights of the Russian-speaking population in
the Baltic countries, Yeltsin said all kinds of Baltic problems
had long been discussed at Russian-Swedish talks.
</P>
<P>
He added that Russia's latest proposals to offer the Baltic
countries security will also be discussed during the visit.
</P>
<P>
In October Yeltsin offered Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania a
security pact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
