<HEADLINE> Exiled Politicians Return to Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, December 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 10 Cambodian
politicians, who have been exiled since last July, today returned
to the country from Thai capital of Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The politicians, who were greeted at the airport by Lakhan
Mehotra, special envoy of United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, were all members of the Union of Cambodian Democrats, which
is made up of the PUNCINPEC, Khmer Buddhist Liberal Democratic
Party, Khmer Nation Party and Khmer Neutral Party.
</P>
<P>
Their purpose of coming back was to pave the way for ousted
Prince Norodom Ranariddh and some other exiled politicians to
return to the country safely and participate in the next year's
national election, they said.
</P>
<P>
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen ousted his rival Ranariddh, then
first prime minister, on July 6 after a weekend of fighting
between troops loyal to the two men. Ranariddh has been exiled
since then.
</P>
<P>
The politicians also asked the U.N to have more influence over
the affairs in Cambodia, so that the election scheduled for next
May will be guaranteed and held in a free, just and democratic way.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen has more than once appealed to the exiled politicians
to come back, but some of them still worried about their safety in
the country.
</P>
<P>
However, Hun Sen insisted that Ranariddh should face the trial
for his violations of law, such as arms smuggling. If convicted,
he will not be allowed to come in for the election before he is
amnestied by the King, Hun Sen added.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh has turned down the offer of the second prime
minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
