<HEADLINE> Foreign Workforce Holds Larger Portion in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 1 (Xinhua) -- There are at least 245,000
foreigners in Israel's workforce this year, compared to 125,000 in
1990, today's local daily Jerusalem Post quoted labor and social
affairs officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
This figure means that more than one in every 10 workers is
non-Israeli.
</P>
<P>
And there is a notable increase in the number of foreign
home-care workers, which has doubled in the past three years and
could reach as many as 15,000 by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Yigal Ben-Shalom, director-general of Labor and Social Affairs
Ministry, said that the Israeli government is taking the issue
very seriously and is trying to lower the number of the foreign
workforce to the level in the early 1990s. 
</P>
