<HEADLINE> Shanghai Textile Enterprise Gears up from Red Operation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Anda Cotton Mill
has successfully reduced huge losses by trimming its work force
and cutting the number of spindles in operation, thereby setting
an excellent example for China's loss-making state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Today's edition of People's Daily, China's leading newspaper,
carried a feature article on Anda's notable progress. The State
Economic and Trade Commission listed the mill as one of the 10
state enterprises that have recorded progress in reducing losses
by deepening reform and improving management. The Chinese media
plans to carry a series of reports on factories contributing to
their success.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai No.10 and No.28 cotton mills were merged to form
Anda in June 1996. Anda originally had 88,000 spindles and
employed 2,139 weavers. The merger was facilitated by the fact
that No.28 Mill suffered 1996 losses of 30 million yuan, but had
idle space for the installation of additional machinery. On the
other hand, the No.10 Mill, the only profitable operation amongst
Shanghai's state textile enterprises, was forced to relocate from
an area designated as part of the financial district in the Pudong
New Area.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's textile authorities decided to merge the two mills
in hopes of creating a stronger player in the market.
</P>
<P>
Fierce competition in the textile market and requirements to
adjust Shanghai's textile industry dictated that the new venture
trim the number of operational spindles and reduce the number
redundant employees in order to survive amidst tough competition
by cutting costs and increasing efficiency. Anda originally had
over 5,000 employees and some 5,200 retirees.
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Textile Enterprise Gears up from Red Operation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An analysis conducted following the merger revealed that 3,000
workers and 52,000 spindles would be sufficient to operate the new
mill.
</P>
<P>
Anda's management team has extended great effort and achieved
notable success in reducing redundant workers. The reemployment
center operated by the Shanghai Textile Holding Co. has helped
1,256 laid-off workers find new job opportunities, thereby
lessening burdens on the enterprise. In addition, Anda has
allocated funds to encourage workers to seek jobs on their own,
with some 500 workers terminating their contracts in order to
begin new careers.
</P>
<P>
The program to reduce the number of spindles proceeded much
more smoothly than the effort to reduce the work force. Anda
optimized its equipment by scrapping 20,000 spindles and
transferring an additional 16,000 units to other plants. The
effort led to marked improvements in terms of both output and
product varieties. Statistics for the first 10 months of the year
showed that Anda had a total yarn output of 6,034
tons. Projections call for 1997 sales to rise by 42.93 percent to
180 million yuan. The company's annual cotton yarn output will
increase 59.75 percent, with the cloth output expected to soar
229.7 percent. Anda also plans to raise salaries for its workers.
</P>
<P>
"Losses between January and October were cut to 187,000 yuan,"
according to Anda Director Chen Guozhen. "We hope to earn a profit
for the year," said Chen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
