<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- More than 5,000 diplomats, scientists and representatives of
non-government organizations started to meet today in Kyoto,
Japan, for a 10-day conference organized by the United Nations on
the reduction of greenhouse gases, held responsible for the global
warming. The center of climatic prevision at Bracknell, Britain,
said on Friday that 1997 will be the hottest year since it began
to measure world temperature in 1860, with temperature being 0.43
degree centigrade higher than the medium between 1961 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
-- The government of Laurent-Desire Kabila of the Democratic
Republic of Congo (ex-Zaire) has expelled the First Secretary of
the French Embassy in Kinshasa, Eric Lubin, accusing him of being
"spy and agent of destabilization." Lubin, who had been in
Kinshasa since January 1996, took the first plane which left
Kinshasa after being declared "persona non grata" and arrived in
Paris Sunday morning from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin Sunday warned the
rightwing oppositions of Rally for the Republic and Union for
French Democracy against the "temptation" presented by the
extreme-right National Front of Jean-Marie Le Pen, who has
suggested establishing alliances between his party and the
oppositions in the local elections to be held in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
