<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Raises Water Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Beijing raised prices for tap
water and sewage treatment today in order to encourage water
conservation and improve the environment.
</P>
<P>
The price of water for private use was raised from 0.5 yuan to
0.7 yuan per ton, with an additional 0.1 yuan sewage treatment
fee, according to a municipal regulation approved by the State
Council.
</P>
<P>
Water prices for enterprises and government organizations was
raised from 0.8 yuan to one yuan per ton, with an accompanying 0.3
yuan sewage treatment fee.
</P>
<P>
The city will no longer collect fees for the use of water
disposal systems, according to the regulation.
</P>
<P>
Prices for underground and surface water resources will also be
adjusted.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has witnessed an extended period of dry weather during
1997, with the precipitation level for the past 11 months falling
by 50 percent on last year's level, according to Liu Hangui,
deputy director of the Beijing Water Conservancy Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The total storage volume for the city's 16 water reservoirs has
dropped by 750 million sq.m., said Liu, adding that the city
currently faces a major water shortage.
</P>
<P>
The price adjustments were introduced to relieve the water
shortage and reduce the hazards of sewage disposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Currency Trading Needs Regulating: Mahathir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad today stressed the need for regulating currency
trading in the interest of everyone for otherwise the economic
damage inflicted on developing economies could spread to the
developed countries as well.
</P>
<P>
"If currency trading is to be allowed, then it should be made
transparent and it should be regulated," he said when opening the
meetings of ASEAN finance ministers and ASEAN Plus Six as well as
the conference on ASEAN Financial Initiatives for the 21st Century
here today.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) finance
ministers and those from Australia, China, Japan, South Korea and
the United States and the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
of China, known as ASEAN Plus Six, began a tow-day meeting here
today to dwell on the current economic situation faced by
countries in the region following recent attacks on their
currencies.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said, "It is ridiculous that at a time when
governments and all other businesses are being exhorted to be open
and transparent, currency trading must be allowed to do their
trading in absolute secrecy."
</P>
<P>
He said, "International trade is being regulated by principles,
policies and regulation agreed to in the World Trade Organization
(WTO). Why should currency trading be exempted from the purview of
the WTO? Why cannot the WTO discuss and formulate rules and
regulation for international currency trading, rules which the
rich and the poor alike have a hand in drawing up, rules which are
fair and just and designed to create wealth and prosperity for
all?"
</P>
<P>
He said currency trading demands to be regulated as every
country would be affected adversely by the uncontrolled currency
trading activities which have left a trail of shattered and
disoriented economies and nations wherever they went.
</P>
<P>
Given these dangers, Mahathir called on the WTO to formulate
and enforce regulations to reduce the anarchy in currency trading
while the International Monetary Fund (IMF) should continue its
supervisory role.
</P>
<P>
He said he saw no reason why currency trading should not be
regulated with fair rules designed to create wealth and prosperity
especially when the worst from currency attacks was not over yet.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said, "There is no conspiracy to dominate the economy
of the developing countries of East Asia, but obviously their
troubles have afforded an opportunity for forcing open their
economies and possible domination by strong and powerful
countries."
</P>
<P>
"We believe in globalization and liberalization of trade, in
dismantling national laws and rules which hamper trade and
cross-border flows of capital. But surely, liberalization and
deregulation of national entities should not result in exposure to
an anarchic world. We have been told to abide by the rule of law,
but how come the abolition of national laws should lead to absence
of the rule of law in the enlarged world market," he said.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meetings, the ASEAN finance ministers and
those from the above-mentioned Six would exchange views on the
causes and extent of the currencies' problem and the policy
responses needed to restore stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, Indonesia, Singapore, the Philippines, Myanmar and
host Malaysia are represented at the meetings by their respective
finance ministers with other ASEAN members Brunei, Vietnam and
Laos by their deputy or vice finance ministers.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN ministers are scheduled to meet representatives from
Japan and the U.S. separately while the ASEAN Ministers Plus Six
would meet IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus and World Bank
Senior Vice President Joseph E. Stiglitz during the meetings.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus was invited to the meeting to brief the ASEAN
ministers on the IMF task force's progress in studying the role of
currency traders and the possibility of introducing prudential
regulations on currency trading.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, the ASEAN finance ministers held a special
meeting here during which they agreed to form a regional
surveillance mechanism within ASEAN as a preventive effort to
avoid the emergence of risk that would precipitate a crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
