<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Filipino-Chinese to Close Business in Protest of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Filipino-Chinese will shut down
their businesses and schools for a day Tuesday in Manila's
Chinatown to protest the killing of a young Filipino-Chinese
businessman by suspected kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
The shutdown will coincide with the burial of Gordon Morales
Tan, 24, who was slain during a botched kidnapping attempt on
November 27, local television Sky Cable said today in its midday
report.
</P>
<P>
The Citizens Action Against Crime, a non-governmental
anti-crime group, was quoted as saying more than one hundred
groups will join the funeral march for Tan in what they called a
"day of mourning" for all the slain kidnap victims.
</P>
<P>
Tan was the latest to die at the hands of kidnappers. Tan was
walking to his car with a security guard in front of his
family-owned shoe factory in Bulucan province north of Manila last
week when four armed men wearing masks tried to force him into
their car.
</P>
<P>
Tan was shot and killed when he resisted. The security guard
was shot and wounded.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time for the Filipino-Chinese community to
resort to a shutdown to protest against the government's
incompetence to smash the rampant kidnapping syndicates. In
January 1993, Chinese schools and business establishments were
also closed for the funeral of a kidnap-for-ransom victim.
</P>
<P>
During the past several months, an upsurge in ransom
kidnappings, mostly of wealthy Filipino-Chinese, was recorded
across the country, prompting President Fidel Ramos to renew a
crackdown on kidnappers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The Citizens Action Against Crime reported last month that
between January and October, there were 116 ransom kidnappings
involving 187 victims nationwide, many of them in the capital and
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
A total of 248 million pesos (8.3 million U.S. dollars) in
ransom has been paid to kidnappers during the period, the group
said. It also warned of more kidnappings of rich businessmen with
Christmas drawing near. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
