<HEADLINE> First High-Level Egyptian Visit to Iran in 18 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister Amr Moussa will
be the first top Egyptian official to visit Iran in 18 years on
Friday, the Middle East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
He will attend a two-day ministerial preparatory meeting for
the 8th Islamic summit to open there on December 9.
</P>
<P>
Tehran severed political ties with Cairo in 1979, the year
Cairo signed its peace treaty with Israel.
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian delegation led by Assistant Foreign Minister Sayed
Kassem al Masri left here today for Tehran to take part in an
expert-level preparatory meetings for the three-day summit.
</P>
<P>
Akhbar Kassimi, official in charge of Iranian affairs in
foreign ministry, said Egypt's presence in the meetings will have
a positive impact on Tehran-Cairo relations which are "proceeding
well."
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old 54-member Organization of Islamic Conference
holds summit every three years. The upcoming summit's agenda
covers various issues facing the Islamic world, mainly the Mideast
peace march and problems in Afghanistan, Bosnia, Somalia, Kashmir,
Iran, and Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
