<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Cards Gaining in Popularity in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Even the elderly in China are
in tune with the electronic money age, and are using credit cards
for their pensions, and credit cards are being used by many
institutions in Beijing and Shanghai, as they enter the lives of
more Chinese with amazing speed.
</P>
<P>
For 10 years, after 1985, when the first credit card appeared
in China, credit cards were a status symbol and a means of showing
one's wealth, because they were not so common.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of China, one of the nation's largest state commercial
banks, has seen use of its "Great Wall" card multiply over the
past several years. During the January-June period this year, the
number of "Great Wall" card users increased 80 percent from the
1996 figure to 50.5 million.
</P>
<P>
The number of places that use credit cards has also grown, and
they now extend beyond the restaurants, hotels, travel agencies,
and shops of the past, to other sectors, and are even being used
to pay various public utility fees.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial and Commercial Bank of China's "Peony Card", had
done 254 billion yuan in business by June, accounting for more
than 30 percent of the total amount of credit card business.
</P>
<P>
People in the higher payscales, like businesspeople, are no
longer the exclusive owners of credit cards, and workers,
low-ranking officials, university students, and even rural people
are all potential customers nowadays.
</P>
<P>
A deputy general manager of the Agricultural Bank of China's
Shanghai Branch says that as many as half of his bank's card
holders live in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
But, even though credit cards are gaining in popularity with
Chinese at unprecedented rates of growth, more needs to be done to
increase their use in China, and some people need three cards from
three different banks just to deal with the inconveniences of a
single card that has a limited number of places where it can be
used.
</P>
<P>
Things are changing. China has ATMs in ten provinces and
municipalities, and the Bank of China set up an information center
on October 30 in Beijing, to form a nationwide network to provide
unified service for different credit cards issued by different
banks.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to have 200 million cards in use by the year
2003, and they may be used in 400 Chinese cities by then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Most of the share prices
declined on the Singapore market while the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index (STII) surged by 33.6 points to close at 1694.19
points today.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that share prices were mixed during the day's
lackluster trading. But the STII increased in the closing minutes
of trade on buying of index-linked stocks.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis in other parts of Asia has led foreign
institutional players to allocate their funds into Singapore, they
noted. One of them said that the money was coming in for
Singapore's safe haven status.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume was low at 131.11 million units, valued at
241.93 million Singapore dollars (about 151.21 million U.S.
dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances by 249 to 89, while 280
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Innovest Bhd was the most actively traded counter as it
registered a turnover of 7.35 million units. It was followed by
Singapore Telecom which had 6.46 million shares traded. Rekapac
was next with 5.65 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Local car distributor Cycle &AMP; Carriage (C&AMP;C) and the Overseas
Chinese Banking Corporation (OCBC) Foreign shared the top spot on
the gainers' list as each of them rose by 40 cents to finish at
7.15 and 9.95 Singapore dollars respectively. Asean Fund and the
United Overseas Bank (UOB) Foreign increased by 35 cents each to
end at nine U.S. dollars and 9.85 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 was the biggest loser as it
declined by 1.1 dollars to close at 43.2 Singapore dollars. IPCO
fell by 80 cents to close at 2.6 U.S. dollars, while Hind Hotels
lost 42 cents to finish at 1.78 Singapore dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
