<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanxi To Set up Museum To Display 2,000-year-old Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A museum to display historical
relics dating back to the Spring and Autumn Period (770-476 B.C.)
will be opened in Houma City in northwest China's Shanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists have discovered more than 140,000 historical
relics in the 40-sq km ruins of the city, the ancient capital of
the Jin State.
</P>
<P>
The historical relics, which include production tools, daily
utensils, sacrificial objects, coins, and treaty documents, will
provide valuable clues for studies of the Jin State's political,
cultural and social activities, as well as military and diplomatic
affairs.
</P>
<P>
The relics also have high archeological value for research on
the period and the transition from a slave society to a feudal
society.
</P>
<P>
The Central government will join local governments and related
departments to open the museum in near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
