<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Nurses Strike Goes on Despite Govt's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Despite the government's order
asking all nurses to immediately resume work or face the sack,
the nurse strike for 500-percent pay hike continued into the
fourth day today, paralyzing most public hospitals around Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The strike, reportedly backed by newly-registered opposition
party Safina and the Kenya Medical Association, simmered the
political atmosphere as it took place on the eve of the December
29 general elections.
</P>
<P>
In a one-page press release issued Sunday, the Kenyan Ministry
of Health canceled all leaves and ordered all nurses to report to
their stations and places of work immediately.
</P>
<P>
"Absence from duty without permission will be regarded as a
gross breach of discipline which may render an officer liable to
summary dismissal with loss of all benefits," the ministry
warned.
</P>
<P>
However, the nurses said they will go on with the strike,
starting from Friday, until their demands for minimum pay of
30,000 Shillings (484 U.S. Dollars) and better allowance are met.
</P>
<P>
"Nurses all over the country have vowed to continue the strike
despite threats issued by the government," said two Nairobi
branch co-ordinators of the strike Joshua Maranga and J.K.
Muiruri later Sunday.
</P>
<P>
On the day, hundreds of striking nurses held a protest rally
in downtown Nairobi. The rally was soon dispersed by anti-riot
policemen using several tear gas canisters.
</P>
<P>
Several nurses claimed to have sustained "soft tissue
injuries" during the rally.
</P>
<P>
At Kenyatta National Hospital in Nairobi, the strike went on
paralyzing all medical services over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, health service in Kisumu District and the Nyanza
Provincial Hospital were not rendered as the health centers
remained deserted, with a few patients being catered for by their
relatives.
</P>
<P>
The nurses could be seen walking in Kisumu, Kenya's
third-largest city bordering on Lake Victoria, but patients at
the hospital said no nurse had reported to the hospital since
Friday, according to local reports available here.
</P>
<P>
Striking nurses at the Nakuru Provincial Hospital, in central
Kenya, chased away students from the Medical Training College who
were assisting patients Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
