<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 08:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Satisfied With New OPEC Oil Export Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait said today it is
satisfied with its newly allocated oil export quota of 2.19
million barrels per day (bpd) starting from next year, comparing
with the current quota of 2 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Kuwaiti Oil Minister Issa Al-Mazidi in an
interview with official Kuwait News Agency before heading back to
Kuwait from Jakarta, Indonesia, where the ministerial conference
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) just
concluded.
</P>
<P>
"Despite differences in views, we managed to raise the (OPEC)
ceiling to 27.5 million bpd and according to which quotas were
distributed and we are satisfied with our just quota," said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
He also praised the spirit of cooperation of OPEC ministers
that led to this positive and "historic results."
</P>
<P>
The oil ministers from 11 OPEC countries had agreed during
their meeting to raise OPEC's production ceiling to 27.5 million
bpd from a previous 25.033 million bpd output for the first six
months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait obtained a 190,000 bpd increase, ranking fifth in quota
hikes after Saudi Arabia with 760,000 bpd, Iran with 340,000 bpd,
Venezuela 230,000 bpd and the United Arab Emirates with 200,000
bpd.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait currently has an oil production capacity of 2.5 million
barrels per day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
