<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Grade Bauxite Mineral Found in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has discovered
high grade bauxite deposits in the eastern Tanga region, Daily
News said today.
</P>
<P>
The deposits, at Magamba area, about six kilometers from
Lushoto town, are estimated to have 50 to 60 million tons of
bauxite -- an ore from which aluminum is made.
</P>
<P>
The discovery was made by a team of geologists led by Medard
Mutakyahwa, a senior lecturer at the University of Dar es Salaam
after an intensive research from the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
According to Mutakyahwa, chemical and mineralogical analysis
made on samples have revealed that bauxite ore found there is 50
to 60 percent aluminum oxide.
</P>
<P>
He said the ore from the deposits had previously been used by
the villagers as ballast material for road construction, but it
was only recently that they discovered the economic importance of
the deposits.
</P>
<P>
These are the first such deposits found in the country, he
said. bauxite is used in the production of aluminum metal,
aluminum sulphate and high grade cement.
</P>
<P>
The research has been helped by a German academic support
agency Daad and the Norwegian Agency for International
Development.
</P>
<P>
He said several private mining companies have shown interest
in the deposits covering an area of 10 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, Tanzania's mineral sector is
currently contributing 1.4 percent of the GDP up from a mere 0.5
percent in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The sector is likely to attract investment of up to 400
million U.S. Dollars by the year 2000. Between 300 and 700
prospecting licenses have been issued to potential investors in
the last few years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
