<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Cases Surge in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The number of people who have
been suffering from AIDS is likely to strike between 23,000 to
30,000 in Vietnam over the next three years, with about
19,000-25,000 dying from the disease, Vietnam press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The new estimate comes from a projected figure of between
140,000 to 180,000 carriers of HIV, the virus which leads to
full-blown AIDS, over the same period.
</P>
<P>
The revelation was made during the first national conference on
HIV/AIDS last month which drew 120 doctors and researchers.
</P>
<P>
The statistics were the results of a survey by a group of
researchers at the Hanoi Epidemiology and Hygiene Institute.
</P>
<P>
The institute reported that HIV has now been found in 57 out of
Vietnam's 61 provinces and cities, and that the incidence of
HIV/AIDS differed from province to province.
</P>
<P>
It said the worst-hit group in An Giang province on the
Cambodian border were prostitutes, whereas most HIV sufferers in
the provinces of Quang Ninh and Lang Son on the Chinese border
were drug addicts.
</P>
<P>
Several researchers reported their findings after interviews
with prostitutes, street children, juvenile delinquents and drug
addicts.
</P>
<P>
To coincide with the International AIDS Day, the Vietnamese
national daily Nhan Dan today carries an editorial, calling for
immediate actions to protect children in a world with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
"We must actively prevent drug abuse and prostitution from
children, raise the awareness against AIDS among the young people,
especially street children," the leading official newspaper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Pharmaceutical Industry Faces Major Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- China's pharmaceutical industry
must rely on high-tech products, a fair competition system and
favorable government policies to meet increasing challenges by the
influx of foreign medicines, according to a major Beijing-based
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Today's Guangming Daily reported that experts at a recent
national conference in Beijing discussed measures to help the
pharmaceutical industry extricate from such a difficult position
that foreign medicines have captured the lion's share of markets
in major Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
The sales volume of imported medinces and those manufactured
by foreign-funded enterprises in China has grown at a phenomenal
rate in recent years. They have now held 59 percent share of the
pharmaceutical market in Beijing, 56 percent in Shanghai and 72
percent in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese experts note that in line with State regulations,
pharmaceutical imports should be limited to products which cannot
be produced in China, which offer better clinical effect than
domestic ones, or which are in shart supplies at home.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, a large quantity of foreign medicines which fail
to conform with the regulations have been imported and sold at
high prices in China, according to Li Bangliang, president of the
Hangzhou East China Pharmaceutical Group.
</P>
<P>
The profit-oriented management systems of most hospitals and
misconceptions on the part of patients have resulted in the
irrational competition in the pharmaceutical industry, said Li.
</P>
<P>
Hospitals prefer to purchase foreign medicines which can be sold
at higher prices and yield greater profits, while domestically
manufactured medicines of the same quality can only be sold at
lower prices. Li added that many patients take it for granted that
"higher priced medicines offer better effect", and thus tend to
use expensive foreign products.
</P>
<P>
Experts called for relevant government departments to establish
a rational competition system, adopt favorable policies to protect
key domestic enterprises and provide support so as to enable them to
introduce advance science and technology to develop high quality
pharmaceuticals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Earn More from Higher Oil Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will earn additional
revenue of about three million U.S. Dollars per day from oil
sales beginning January 1, 1998 as OPEC has raised its production
quota by 177,000 barrels daily.
</P>
<P>
The relief came Saturday night when the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) also re-elected Nigeria's
Rilwanu Lukman to a second three-year term as secretary-general,
the Daily Champion reported today.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the raise of Nigeria's production quota, the first in
over four years, the country's share had been 1.865 million
barrels per day, but from January 1 next year, the allocation
would become 2.042 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at the OPEC ministerial council meeting
in Jakarta, Indonesia at the weekend. The council agreed to raise
the total OPEC production to 27.5 million barrels per day from
the current 25.033 million with effect from January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The new quota, effective for six months in the first instance,
would be reconsidered at the next OPEC ministerial council
meeting on June 24 next year in Vienna, Austria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
