<HEADLINE> Japan to Consider Using Public Funds for Credit Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto said today that his government will consider the use of
public funds to keep the country's credit order intact, Kyodo News
service reported.
</P>
<P>
"We will take all available measures to stabilize the financial
system, which is the cornerstone of the economy," Hashimoto said
during a session of the House of Representatives (lower house)
Budget Committee.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions from former Prime Minister Kiichi Miyazawa,
Hashimoto reiterated the government's firm commitment to
protecting all assets of depositors and investors as well as
wiping away concerns over financial unrest.
</P>
<P>
Miyazawa heads a special task force on financial system
stabilization of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), which
is due to unveil a set of measures to maintain the health of
Japan's financial system around December 10.
</P>
<P>
Confidence in Japan's financial system has been severely
weakened following a series of collapses last month of four
financial institutions, including Yamaichi Securities Co. and
Hokkaido Takushoku Bank.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto also expressed readiness to freeze the land value tax
so as to promote transactions in the lackluster property market.
</P>
<P>
To reinvigorate the sagging stock market, Hashimoto hinted once
again at a review of the securities transaction tax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
