<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiamen Records Foreign Trade Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Xiamen in southeast China's
Fujian Province recorded a foreign trade volume of over 6.5
billion US dollars for the first ten months of this year, up some
15 percent on the previous year's period.
</P>
<P>
The figure included exports of over 3.4 billion US dollars, up
21 percent on the 1996 period, and imports of 3.1 billion US
dollars, up eight percent.
</P>
<P>
Local state-owned enterprises contributed 2.9 billion US
dollars, or 44 percent, of the foreign trade volume, up sightly on
the 1996 figure of 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
The city's foreign-funded enterprises recorded an 18 percent
rise in exports to 1.69 billion US dollars, with imports rising
slightly by 0.5 percent to 1.67 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dramatic import tariff reductions in October sparked a 42
percent surge in imports for the processing sector when compared
to the same month in 1996. The sector's foreign trade volume of
3.1 billion US dollars accounted for nearly half of the total for
the city.
</P>
<P>
Machinery, electronic and textile products accounted for the
bulk of exports, with imports consisting mostly of machinery,
electronic components, and plastic and textile raw materials and
products.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen's major overseas trade partners are Hong Kong and
Taiwan, with most exports going to the former and the bulk of
imports coming from the latter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
