<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 09:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Says No Change in its Policy on Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran has announced that it
recognizes the government of President Burhanuddin Rabbani as
the legal government of Afghanistan and there has been no change
in this policy.
</P>
<P>
Iran's special representative on Afghanistan Alaeddin
Boroujerdi voiced Tehran's stance Sunday evening on the eve of a
congress of Afghan outstanding personalities to be held today in
Iran's central city of Isfahan, the Iranian official news agency
IRNA reported today.
</P>
<P>
This policy is in line with the international stand adopted
by the United Nations, said Boroujerdi, the former deputy
foreign minister on Asia-Pacific affairs.
</P>
<P>
He said that the policy followed by Iran throughout the
crisis in Afghanistan was the right approach chosen by the
U.N. and even the countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
On the congress of Afghan leading personalities in Isfahan,
Boroujerdi said this congress demonstrated Iran's policy which
supports any steps taken toward an overall understanding and
peace in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He said many leading Afghan personalities representing various
tribes would participate in the three-day congress and hold
talks on ways to end the crisis in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
IRNA reported that Rabbani arrived in Isfahan Sunday night to
take part in the congress.
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi said that Iran has welcomed the U.N. proposal to
hold a conference of the countries neighboring Afghanistan to
review ways to implement peace in that country and was prepared
to host such talks.
</P>
<P>
About Afghanistan's seat remaining vacant at the Summit of
the Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC) to be held here
on December 9-11, Boroujerdi said Rabbani would be welcomed as an
official guest in Tehran, but the occupation of Afghanistan's
seat at the summit was determined by the OIC and has been left
vacant in accordance with a decision made at the Jakarta
conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
