<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea, IMF Continue Negotiations on Terms of Bailout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government and
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) are continuing their
negotiations on the terms of IMF's bailout for Seoul, particularly
on South Korea's macro-economic growth range.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean Ministry of Finance and Economy said Monday
morning that the two sides at Sunday midnight reached an agreement
in principle on terms of the rescue package and the agreement is
waiting for approvals by the South Korean cabinet and the IMF
special board meeting today.
</P>
<P>
However, South Korean Deputy Prime Minister Lim Chang-yuel and
IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus continued their
negotiations on differences at some points concerning the terms of
the loan.
</P>
<P>
In their telephone negotiations Monday morning, Michel
Camdessus, who is attending a meeting of Asian finance ministers
in Kuala Lumpur, insisted on demanding that Seoul reduce its gross
domestic product rate to 2.5 percent, a ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
But Minister Lim upheld the figure at three percent, citing the
possible social unstability due to the high jobless rate, said the
official.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two sides also showed differences on issues of
liquidating troubled financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
While the IMF side strongly demanded that 12 insolvent merchant
banks be liquidated, the South Korean side wants softer measures
on the issue, asking to leave the issue for further negotiation
after the loan arrives in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government wishes to complete the agreement on
the terms during today and then hand it to the IMF for approval,
paving the way for the earlier arrival of the first tranche of
about 10 billion U.S. dollars this week.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is the third recipient in Asia of IMF funds after
Thailand and Indonesia since August following a wave of steep
currency depreciations caused by massive debt overhangs in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
