<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Rationing Starts in Philippine Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Water rationing started today in
the eastern section of the Philippine capital area as the dry
spell generated by the El Nino phenomenon continues to take its
toll in many parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Water rationing in Metro Manila was ordered late last month by
President Fidel Ramos as the water level at the Angat reservoir
had dropped to 182 meters, 21 meters below the normal level of at
least 200 meters.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir, located in Bulacan province north of Manila,
provides 97 percent of water supply to the capital city. The
critical level is placed at 170 meters.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Manila Water Service Inc. were quoted today by
local television reports as saying the 12-hour rotation of water
services is just one of two kinds of rationing options of the
company to counter the effects of the weather disturbance.
</P>
<P>
Some areas of eastern Metro Manila will have water from 4 a.m.
to 4 p.m., while water will be available in other areas between 4
p.m. and 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
The other option is to use firetrucks in supplying water to
areas hardest hit by the water reduction scheme, such as hospitals
and clinics.
</P>
<P>
Also, starting today the Metro Manila police will conduct foot
and mobile patrol to monitor the illegal and excessive use of
water.
</P>
<P>
But the water rationing plan has not yet started in the west
zone of Metro Manila, where water is supplied by Maynilad Water
Services, the other concessionaire water distribution company.
</P>
<P>
The capital area's water supply and sewerage system were
privatized in May this year. Maynilad Water Services and Manila
Water Service Inc. are the two concessionaires running the system.
</P>
<P>
The water rationing was recommended by the El Nino Task Force
as a contingency measure against the drought brought about by the
El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The Manila Waterworks and Sewerage System earlier approved a
plan by the two private firms to cut daily water distribution by
nearly one third starting next January so as to stretch Metro
Manila's water supply until the onset of the next rainy season.
</P>
<P>
El Nino, which began to affect the Philippines and its
neighboring nations in the middle of this year, is expected to
last until the mid-1998 and bring severe dry spells to the
country.
</P>
<P>
El Nino, a weather phenomenon developing in the southern
Pacific, is associated with many kinds of abnormal weather
activities around the globe, such as severe drought, heavy
flooding and violent storm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
