<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Gets Contract From Democratic Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has won a "special"
lucrative contract order for about two billion Zimbabwean Dollars
(140 million U.S. Dollars) to export dry food rations, and other
military supplies to the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The Herald daily quoted secretary and marketing manager of the
Zimbabwean Defense Industries Company Douglas Mrewa said in an
interview at the weekend that the DRC was now treated as a
special order and therefore was handled separately from others
because their orders were enormous.
</P>
<P>
The company was awarded the contract to supply the military
supplies, and specifically food, for as long as possible because
the DRC was on its path to recovery and was anxious to feed its
estimated 45 million people, Mrewa said.
</P>
<P>
The military supplies include army uniforms and boots and
other foodstuffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
