<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Activist Gets Award in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese companies
recently purchased insurance policies valued at 1.7 million yuan
to reward Guo Zhenqing's efforts in uncovering fake merchandise.
</P>
<P>
Guo, 32, has used much of his spare time in helping unlucky
consumers get compensation after having been cheated by dishonest
merchants - free of charge.
</P>
<P>
Each year, Guo has helped resolve about 100 economic disputes
and provided free advice to some 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
But, when he sees fake commodities being sold in certain
stores, he prefers to warn the manager first to get him stop the
illegal business rather than buying the goods and then asking for
compensation.
</P>
<P>
"Enterprises have the same interest as consumers in getting rid
of fake goods in the marketplace," said one of the two companies,
the Little Swan Group, a major washing-machine manufacturer in
China. The Little Swan Group bought an insurance policy valued at
1.5 million yuan for Guo.
</P>
<P>
The Ping'an Insurance Company's Shijiazhuang branch purchased
an insurance policy worth of 200,000 yuan for Guo, saying it
believes consumers who devote themselves to keeping order in the
marketplace should get more supports.
</P>
<P>
Guo now has been invited by the two enterprises to serve as a
quality-control and service supervisor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
