<HEADLINE> Two Kenyan Opposition Parties to Join Hands in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Democratic Party of Kenya (DP)
and FORD-Kenya, two leading opposition parties in the country,
have struck a deal of supporting single candidates in each civic
and parliamentary seat in a bid to win this month's elections.
</P>
<P>
DP leader Mwai Kibaki and FORD-Kenya national co-ordinator
Jackson Kibor said in Kitale, western Kenya Sunday the two
parties can only effectively challenge ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU) if they approach the poll jointly.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kibaki, also DP's presidential candidate, ruled out
involving KANU in a unity government should his party win the
December 29 elections.
</P>
<P>
Kibor said he supported the unity of opposition parties but
hit out at FORD-Asili presidential aspirant Martin Shikuku for
allegedly being a stumbling block to the unity.
</P>
<P>
In general, opposition parties' division is deepening as the
poll approaches despite the new joint deal between DP and
FORD-Kenya.
</P>
<P>
National Development Party (NDP) presidential aspirant Raila
Odinga, in a speech at a rally in Meru Saturday, dismissed his
opposition presidential rivals as dormant and opportunists, and
urged the voters to reject them.
</P>
<P>
He said fellow opposition presidential candidates, including
Kibaki, Shikuku, Charity Ngilu and Wamalwa Kijana (FORD-Kenya),
have manifested an image that they are sure to personally benefit
without minding the welfare of people.
</P>
<P>
Kenya National congress (KNC) Chairman Chibule wa Tsuma
claimed in Mombasa Sunday his party has rejected Ngilu's bid to
vie for the presidency on its tickets because she did not want to
follow procedures.
</P>
<P>
In another development, confusion, complaints and celebrations
marked the KANU nomination following the party headquarters'
order of repeats in 21 constituencies today, leaving political
careers of three Kenyan cabinet ministers to hang in the balance.
</P>
</TEXT>
