<HEADLINE> Winter Olympic Organisers To End Downhill Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Nagano Winter Olympics organising
committee (NAOC) will reach a compromise plan on Monday to raise
the starting point of the men's downhil course after four years of
bickering poised to shadow the Games.
</P>
<P>
"We will basically accept it," Nagano governor Goro Yoshimura,
also one of NAOC's vice chairmen, said before reporters , "I think
NAOC will also accept it."
</P>
<P>
Russi, the new course designer for the International Ski
Federation (FIS), plans to start the course at 1,765 meters above
sea level, skim the snaking boundary of the park at one point and
jump over at another point.
</P>
<P>
The FIS has demanded the start point of the top ski event be
raised from 1,680 meters above sea level to 1,800 meters on Mount
Karamatsu to prevent the Nagano course being the shortest in
Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
But the secretariat of the NAOC opposed the higher start for
encroaching onto the protected national park where Japan's
evironment laws will ban any construction.
</P>
<P>
NAOC's Secretariat meanwhile insisted that an additional
stretch should skirt outside the reserve -- down a narrow strip
by the edge of the mountain dotted with towers for ski
lifts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
