<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unemployed Chinese Couple Show How To Start Profitable Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A couple who were among the
thousands of people laid off their jobs in the city of Baotou in
north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region four years ago,
managed to earn 20,000 yuan, or 2,400 US dollars, last year.
</P>
<P>
Liu Huanmei and her husband, Zhang Qing, found themselves
unemployed for the first time when the food company they were
working for was approaching bankruptcy. They had to manage to
adapt to days of unemployment, she says, but would think of the
machines in the factory.
</P>
<P>
And, to make matters worse, their savings were not enough to
feed them for a long time. they had to find a way with their own
initiative, so Liu and her husband found a profitable business in
chickens.
</P>
<P>
They sold their house and other property and borrowed 20,000
yuan, 100 times the couple's total monthly income, to begin their
new endeavor.
</P>
<P>
At their makeshift farm, they started raising chickens, but
their lack of experience and technology cost them 15,000 yuan in
two consecutive failures.
</P>
<P>
They encouraged each other and tried to get a lesson from each
failure and ultimately succeeded, and the farm now has 5,000
chickens.
</P>
<P>
In addition to that, they were able to help support their
former fellow workers with a chicken-breeding business near a coal
mine.
</P>
<P>
In China, there are at least nine million of these unemployed
workers who are trying to find new work by using different means
like the one Liu and her husband used. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Rated World's Freest Economy Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is rated the freest
 economy in the world four months after it became a Special
Administrative Region (SAR) of China, according to the 1998 Index
of Economic Freedom, released here today by the Washington-based
Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has topped the list of the freest economy for the
fourth year in a row, said an editor of the Index, a 408-page
survey that rates economic freedom in 156 of the world's 190
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Kim Holmes, co-editor of the Index report, told a press
briefing here today that Hong Kong's transition from British rule
to a Chinese SAR has done nothing to alter Hong Kong's status as
the world's most open setting to purse economic activities.
</P>
<P>
"(According to) hat we have seen developing over the last few
months, there doesn't seem to be any indication that there is
fundamental change in Hong Kong's economy," said Holmes, who is
vice president of the Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The annual index survey said that there continues to be little
government interference in the market place in Hong Kong, where
taxes remain low and predictable, foreign trade still is free and
regulation still is transparent.
</P>
<P>
Even the recent currency turmoil has not affected Hong Kong's
economic fundamentals much, said Holmes.
</P>
<P>
Singapore ranks second in the 1998 Index of Economic Freedom,
said the annual survey, which measures ten economic factors
ranging from trade policy, taxation to monetary policy, banking
and regulation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
