<HEADLINE> HK Shoppers Spend 20m HKD in Yaohan Clearance Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A total sum of 20 million HK
dollars (2.56 million U.S. dollars) was spent in the two-day
clearance sale of Yaohan's nine local stores for heavily
discounted goods, it was estimated.
</P>
<P>
About 30,000 shoppers turned up on Sunday at the Yaohan stores
for the last day of the chain's closure sale, bringing to 130,000
the total number of shoppers in the cash-only weekend frenzy,
according to provisional liquidators Earnst and Young.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that an average of one to two million HK
dollars (120,000 to 250,000 U.S. dollars) was spent in each of the
stores, for products discounted by up to 60 percent, local
newspapers said. Some of the goods were sold for just 20 percent
of their full price.
</P>
<P>
But most of the stores closed earlier than the scheduled time,
with Tsuen Wan, the first Yaohan store to sell out yesterday,
closing its doors at 1:30 PM.
</P>
<P>
Earnst and Young partner Matthew O'Driscoll put the figures of
local shoppers at about 100,000 customers on Saturday and around
30 percent of that amount on Sunday. Although large queues formed
outside the stores early Saturday, but much less bargain-hunters
turned out on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Policemen were assigned to the stores to keep order and offer
help.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Yaohan Department Store Limited announced its closure
two weeks ago as it was unable to pay rent or suppliers, after
losing up to 100 million HK dollars (12.82 million U.S. dollars) a
year for the past three years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
