<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Project Secures Energy Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- China's decision to build
cross-century strategic energy bases is the key to safeguarding
China's energy security in the 21st century, and to date the
pursuit of this policy has born fruit, Today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
The "Shenhua Project" has been designed by China to strengthen
its cross-century energy base, and frequently compared to China's
"Three Gorges Project."
</P>
<P>
To date, two phases of the Shenhua Project have essentially
been completed. The annual coal production capacity of the
Shenfu-Dongsheng coal fields located in the northeast of Shaanxi
Province and the south of the Inner Mongolia Automonous Region has
reached 30 million tons, and the construction of the
198-kilometer-long Shenbao and Shenhuang railways in northern
China's Hebei Province has been finished.
</P>
<P>
The third phase of the project, which has recently begun,
includes enhancement of current coal production capacity to 60
million tons, the building of the Huanghua harbor for shipping
coal and the construction of Huanghua power station.
</P>
<P>
Completion of the Shenhua Project by 2005 will dramatically
ease tensions in China's energy supply for a long time to come and
help promote expansion of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Government attaches much importance to the project
and has granted preferential policies to the Shenhua Group, which
was organized in October 1995 to take charge of the project.
</P>
<P>
The group aims to help address the problems in China's
coal-production industry and develop into a giant multinational
group company that does business in different sectors such as
energy, transportation, finance and trade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soeharto Urges OPEC Countries To Unite In Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
today called on member countries of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) to maintain their unity a time when
they are faced with both challenges and opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to oil ministers from OPEC's 11 member states at the
closing ceremony of the 103rd OPEC Ministerial Meeting here,
Soeharto said the oil market is becoming increasingly competitive.
</P>
<P>
Oil-producing countries, including OPEC members, can no longer
expect a huge profit from a rise in oil prices, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the challenges awaiting OPEC members in developing the
oil industry are becoming more difficult to cope with, although
energy tax policies are being adopted, particularly by developed
countries, to preserve the environment.
</P>
<P>
One of the challenges is the rapid development of various types
of non-oil energies, including new and renewable energies. The
increasingly high production of non-OPEC nations poses another
challenge, Soeharto said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, it is a challenge in itself for OPEC member
states to maintain the present level of production, while
preserving their reserves.
</P>
<P>
Despite these challenges, chances remain open to continue oil
development and OPEC can play an even greater role in it, he said.
</P>
<P>
The far greater oil reserves of OPEC members compared to
non-OPEC countries allow OPEC members to raise production and this
will go on for a long period, Soeharto said.
</P>
<P>
"Oil also remains dominant for a relatively long time, due to
its superior character unchallenged by other energy sources," he
added.
</P>
<P>
OPEC's Secretary General Dr. Rilwanu Lukman told a press
conference later that the OPEC meeting, which started on November
26, has decided to raise the OPEC production ceiling for the first
half of 1998 to 27.5 million barrels per day (bpd) from the
current 25.033 million bpd.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also unanimously elected Indonesian Mines and
Energy Minister Ida Bagus Sudjana as OPEC's President for six
months and extended the tenure of Lukman as Secretary General for
another three years, effective from 1st January 1998.
</P>
<P>
The ministers reviewed the secretary general's report, the
report of the Economic Commission Board, the report of the
Ministerial Monitoring Subcommittee and various administrative
matters.
</P>
<P>
The conference also approved the budget of the organization for
the year 1998.
</P>
<P>
Lukman said resolutions adopted at the conference will be
published on December 29, after ratification by member countries.
</P>
<P>
The next ordinary meeting of the conference will be held in
Vienna on June 24, 1998, said Lukman.
</P>
<P>
OPEC groups Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Libya,
Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Nigeria, and
Venezuela.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nations Meet to Seek Ways of Curbing Global Warming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. climate conference opened
today in Kyoto, Japan, to explore ways of curbing global warming,
Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The 10-day conference, attended by 5,000 delegates from some
170 countries, will seek to set greenhouse gas emission targets
for developed nations and discuss the role of developing countries
in the fight.
</P>
<P>
Tough negotiations are expected at the meeting as wide
differences remain on both issues.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Environment Agency chief Hiroshi Oki called for
forging a worldwide strategy to tackle global warming.
</P>
<P>
Japan said that industrialized nations should aim at 5 percent
as their basic but flexible target for cutting average annual
emissions from 1990 levels between 2008 to 2012.
</P>
<P>
The United States, the world's largest emitter of greenhouse
gases, wants to stabilize such emissions at 1990 levels in the
specified period.
</P>
<P>
The European Union calls on these nations to cut greenhouse gas
emissions by 15 percent from 1990 levels by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo urged Washington to raise its reduction target but
regarded the EU proposal unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
Carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases, produced mainly
through combustion of oil, coal and other fossil fuels, are blamed
for increasing the earth's temperature by trapping heat in the
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have warned that global warming will cause frequent
occurrence of droughts, an increase in infectious diseases and a
rise in sea level which can submerge island countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
