<HEADLINE> Visitor Arrivals in S'pore May See Near Zero Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Visitor arrivals in Singapore
may come to a standstill as the Singapore Tourism Board (STB) is
expecting "near zero" growth in visitor arrivals this year, the
Business Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
A "near zero" arrivals growth this year would be the lowest in
14 years, way below the earlier estimate of three to five percent
increase, it said.
</P>
<P>
The revision in forecast had been widely expected by industry
members given that in the first ten months this year, visitor
arrivals increased only by 1.2 percent compared with a year ago.
</P>
<P>
An STB spokesman was quoted as saying that due to the adverse
effects of the haze and the regional currency turmoil, the Board
could expect a near zero growth in visitor arrivals for 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, as for the industrial prospects for 1998, some market
analysts were not optimistic as they expect flat, if not negative,
growth in the year to come.
</P>
<P>
The Business Times report quoted a hotel consultant and
research analyst as saying that visitor arrivals next year might
be less than this year because spending had been pinched in the
key markets of Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand, Japan and South
Korea, all significant markets for Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Another analyst was even looking at as low as a five percent
contraction in 1998 visitor arrivals, while the problem, the
report noted, was also compounded by a growing supply of hotel
rooms.
</P>
<P>
STB figures showed that the number of gazetted hotel rooms will
grow by another four percent in 1997, six percent in 1998, and
four to five percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
As a result, hotel occupancy is expected to fall to 75 percent
in 1998, down from 82 percent last year, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
