<HEADLINE> India, Bangladesh Agree on Status Quo in Disputed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 1 (Xinhua)-- India and Bangladesh have
agreed to maintain a status quo in the disputed border areas till
a final decision on the issue, official sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
There are four disputed areas along the 856-km-long Indo-Bangla
border with India's Tripura state in the far east of the country.
These are Muhuri Char, Khowai, Feni and Jaleya in South and West
Tripura districts.
</P>
<P>
The decision to maintain status quo in the disputed areas was
taken recently at a five-day meeting between Indian Border
Security Forces (BSF) and Bangladesh Rifles. The meeting was held
in Dhaka, capital of Bangladesh, from October 14 to 18.
</P>
<P>
At the Dhaka meeting, while BSF officials expressed concern
that Indian militants setting up base camps in Bangladesh were
attacking the security forces and civilians of Tripura and other
northeastern states, the Bangladesh officials expressed their
anxiety over the smuggling of drugs from India into Bangladesh.
</P>
</TEXT>
