<HEADLINE> Nepali Economy Faces Threat of Collapse: Economists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The poor economy of Nepal
faces a threat of collapse unless the huge foreign capital is
invested in productive sectors, Nepali newspapers today quoted
economists as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nepal currently owes 160 billion rupees (about 2.6 billion U.S.
dollars) in foreign loans, which means 8,000 rupees (about 131
dollars) for each citizen, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
"The huge amount of foreign capital we have been drawing must
be used in productive sectors, otherwise our economy will
collapse," warned Dr. Yubaraj Khatiwada, an economic advisor with
the Nepal Rastra Bank, the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
MP Hari Rokka, an economist, also told a function organized by
the Nepal Relation Society that too much loans will "put us into
financial crisis" as 90 percent of Nepal's annual budget depends
on foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Bal Gopal Vaidya, ex-member of Nepal's National Planning
Commission, said the loans Nepal owes increased twice due to the
consistent devaluation of the Nepali currency.
</P>
<P>
But "terrible situations will emerge if loans are stopped at
present," he added.
</P>
<P>
Nepal's gross national product (GNP) in the fiscal year 1994-95
was 205.1 billion rupees (about 3.5 billion dollars), with per
capita GNP standing at 9,766 rupees (about 168 dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
