<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 1 (Xinhua) -- India's care-taker Prime
Minister Inder Kumar Gujral today called upon all sections of
society in the country to be actively involved in AIDS awareness
activities on a continuing basis from the World AIDS Day on
December 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The call was contained in his message to mark the World AIDS
Day throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Indian Minister of State for Health and Family Welfare Renuka
Chowdhury said in her message that the epidemic of HIV-ADIS
continues to spread in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Today at least 70,000 people are HIV positive and about 5,000
have developed full blown AIDS. AIDS affects not just individuals
in our societies but the nation's economic productivity," she
said.
</P>
<P>
"We must confront the issues that lead to the spread of
HIV/AIDS with determination and compassion-determination to spread
awareness and encourage responsible personal behavior and
compassion for those suffering from HIV/AIDS," she said.
</P>
<P>
The first case of AIDS in India was registered in 1986. Since
then, HIV prevalence has been reported in all states and Union
territories.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the first case of AIDS was registered in the country
in 1986, a National AIDS Committee was set up and the government
launched the National AIDS Control Program in the following year
focusing on increasing awareness of HIV/AIDS, screening of blood
for HIV, and testing of individuals practicing risk behaviors.
</P>
