<HEADLINE> Conference Appeals Jobs For AIDS Sufferers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 30 (Xinhua) -- When AIDS sufferers combat their
disease with new therapies and get significantly longer life
expectancy, they may also want to get back into normal jobs.
</P>
<P>
Italian organizations combating this disease will be thinking
about projects to help them return to work, which also means
breaking down the barriers of prejudice at the work place.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a two-day conference on HIV positive here Saturday
in view of Monday's World AIDS Day, Fiore Crespi, newly elected
chairman of Anlaids, a leading anti-AIDS organization, announced
the creation of a permanent observatory for violations of the
rights of HIV positive and AIDS sufferers.
</P>
<P>
The conference was attended by 50 scientists from France,
Italy, Israel, the Netherlands, Russia, Spain, the United States
and Switzerland. It was organized by UNESCO, the World AIDS
Research and Prevention Council, the Italian National Research
Council, and the National Health Institute.
</P>
<P>
The participants discussed survival of child AIDS sufferers,
the therapy for pregnant mothers and the problems of AIDS orphans.
</P>
<P>
Since the first reported death of a child by AIDS in Los
Angeles 15 years ago, almost three million children under 15 are
estimated to have caught the disease worldwide, and at least a
thousand are dying each day. 
</P>
