<HEADLINE> Thai Government Urged to Aid More to HIV/AIDS Schemes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government and private
sector have been urged to provide more financial help to those
infected by HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Dares Chusri, coordinator of the Non-governmental Organizations
Coalition on AIDS of Thailand, expressed concern that financial
support on activities related to the war on AIDS have shrunk.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government-sponsored NGO budget for AIDS has been cut
from 80 million baht (2 million US dollars) last year to 60
million baht (1.5 million dollars) this year, the Bangkok Post
today quoted her as saying on the occasion of World AIDS Day
today.
</P>
<P>
She said foreign donors have also diverted their support to
less-developed Indochinese countries.
</P>
<P>
She said if nothing is done to continue the fight against AIDS,
the number of HIV-positive people in Thailand could exceed 1.3
million by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The official HIV-positive estimate at present is 800,000.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that of the one million children born annually
in the country, at least 20,000 will be born to HIV-positive
mothers. Of these, at least 20 percent will die before the age of
two, while the rest will risk social, economic and psychological
discriminations caused by their parents' AIDS status.  
</P>
