<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Cut Tariffs on Feed Raw Materials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Commerce Ministry will
reduce import tariffs on raw materials used in animal feed
production next year, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The tariff on soybean meal will be lowered to 3 percent from 5
percent, while that on fish meal with a protein content more than
60 percent will be reduced to 6 percent from 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministry will scrape the 350 baht (8.75 U.S.
dollars) surcharge on fish meal per ton and the 180 baht (4.5
dollars) surcharge per ton on maize outside import quota.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's planned move to cut the tariffs is aimed at
lowering the animal feed cost and bringing down the prices on the
domestic market.
</P>
<P>
According to the forecasts by the Internal Trade Department
under the ministry, Thailand's demand for animal feed would reach
11.94 million tons in 1998, up 3.84 percent from this year.
</P>
<P>
Demand for maize in 1998 will be up 1.2 percent year-on-year to
4.7 million tons, while demand for soybean will rise by 3.9
percent to 1.5 million tons and demand for fish meal will climb up
6 percent to 886,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Thailand needs to import some 551,000 tons of maize next year
as its maize output for the year is estimated at 4.15 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that it currently plans to import 300,000
tons of maize initially at a zero tariff rate during a time limit
from January to June next year.
</P>
<P>
If that amount is not enough, the ministry will allow more
imports.
</P>
<P>
Thailand also needs to import at least 800,000 tons of soybean
meal as its domestic output was estimated at only 691,524 tons.
</P>
<P>
Officials said that the ministry had not set a limit on soybean
meal imports this year and this policy will continue next year,
except the tariff cut from 5 percent to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Thailand is expected to import more than 415,000
tons of fish meal next year, as its domestic output was expected
to be merely around 470,000 tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
