<HEADLINE> China's Machinery Exports Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Exports of machinery and
electrical products jumped 23.7 percent in the first nine months
of this year over the same period of 1996, according to today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The increase suggests China's economic strength amid a
string of financial turmoil battering some Asian countries, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Central Administration of Customs show that
the trade volume of machinery and electrical products topped 80
billion U.S. dollars, up 9.2 percent from the same period of the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, exports hit 41.03 billion U.S. dollars, up 23.7
percent, while imported machinery and electrical products were
down 2.7 percent, standing at 39.03 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exports of vessels, power generators and electric motors and
some electronics products saw dramatic double-digit rises while TV
sets, containers and electric fans shipped abroad declined
considerably.
</P>
<P>
The structure of exports improved greatly, with exports of such
high technology products as integrated circuits, micro-electronics
components, converters, motorcycles, and numerically controlled
machine tools growing sharply, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Imports of forklifts, elevators, food-processing machinery, and
rubber and plastics manufacturing equipment slumped
significantly. However, the imports of components for power
generating equipment and computer parts and semi-conductors
climbed to a new high, 6.6 billion U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
