<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hondurans Go to Polls, Opposition Complains of Irregularities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Hondurans voted today for
a new president while the opposition party complained of
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
The voters will also choose three vice presidents, all 128
congressional deputies, 20 deputies to the Central American
parliament and 297 municipal officials.
</P>
<P>
Both front-runners in the presidential field of five candidates
are conservative. Carlos Flores Facusse from the ruling Liberal
Party is widely expected to win.
</P>
<P>
Nora de Melgar of the National Party is the first woman to seek
the presidency of this Central American nation of 5.8 million
people.
</P>
<P>
A CID-Gallup poll done last week put Flores at 48 percent
against Melgar's 31 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other presidential contenders include candidates from the
social democratic Party of Innovation and Unity (PINU), the
Christian Democratic Party (PDC), and for the first time, a
cluster of left-wing parties in the Democratic Unification (UD)
coalition.
</P>
<P>
The front runners have few political differences: both favor
conservative economic policies and populist social agendas, and
both have pledged to open the economy, decentralize the federal
government, and fight poverty and corruption.
</P>
<P>
A recent Gallup poll shows that 33 percent of Hondurans believe
that crime is the country's main problem. Nineteen percent believe
that poverty is more serious, and 14 percent said it was
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Flores, 47, is the current head of Congress. He is also owner
of La Tribuna, the highest circulation newspaper in the country.
</P>
<P>
Melgar, 56, is the widow of a general who overthrew a military
government in 1975. She comes from a wealthy ranching family and
is a former mayor of Tegucigalpa.
</P>
<P>
While no serious incidents were reported, Rafael Callejas, a
former president and leader of the opposition National Party, said
that some people who should have been ineligible to vote were
allowed to cast ballots because lists of people to be barred from
the election had not been delivered in time.
</P>
<P>
The National Election Tribunal (TNE) last week authorized
voters to use outdated identification cards after determining that
about 300,000 voters -- out of a total of 2.9 million -- would not
have their new cards in time to vote on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The new president will take office on January 27, 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
