<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Hotels in Sanctuary Warned of Rebel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan defense
authorities have cautioned hotel managers in the southern
sanctuary of Yala to be cautious of rebel infiltration following
the arrest of six Tamil rebel suspects Saturday, according to
reports reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The six, including a woman, were arrested by the security
forces in the Yala Wild Life Sanctuary, Southern province, where
rebels of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) had been
active during recent months.
</P>
<P>
Three of them could not produce their identity cards to police.
</P>
<P>
Defense sources said LTTE rebels were trying to infiltrate into
the Yala jungles and the Kataragama area in the south due to the
military offensives by government troops in the north.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry thus asked hotel managers in those areas
to be vigilant over suspicious people seeking accommodation.
</P>
<P>
Residents living around the sanctuary were also warned of rebel
activities in the area.
</P>
<P>
LTTE rebels had burnt down some of the bungalows in the
sanctuary, hijacked tourist vehicles and held wild life department
workers and fishermen in neighboring villages as hostages in the
past months.
</P>
<P>
Consequently the police and the Army launched a major operation
to flush out the rebels from the sanctuary.  
</P>
</TEXT>
