<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Bourse Allows Wider Daily Price Movements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Beginning today, the Stock
Exchange of Thailand (SET) will allow the price of each stock to
rise or fall by up to 30 percent a day, an increase from the
former 10-percent limit.
</P>
<P>
All trading will halt for one hour if the main SET index falls
in a day by 100 points from the previous trading day.
</P>
<P>
Stock market analysts believe that the new rules will make
playing stocks more risky than ever.
</P>
<P>
SET President Singh Tangtatswas said at weekend that the new
regulations "increase the chances for both profits and gains" but
also warned investors that they must be well prepared before they
enter the market.
</P>
<P>
SET regulators insisted that the wider daily price-movement
ceilings and floors for common stocks are necessary for long-term
development of the market, but also cautioned that retail
investors should closely monitor price trends to prevent sudden
losses.
</P>
<P>
Paiboon Ratniyom, an analyst with Asia Securities Trading, said
that while the expanded trading limits are unlikely to spur the
market out of its sluggishness, the changes will bring the SET
closer to international practices.
</P>
<P>
However, in order to curb wild downturns on the market, new
"circuit breakers" will be implemented at the SET beginning today.
If the SET index falls more than 100 points from the previous
day's close, all trading will be temporarily halted for one hour.
</P>
<P>
If the index drops more than 150 points, a delay of 90 minutes
will be imposed; and trading will be canceled for the rest of the
day if the index falls more than 200 points.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts predicted that little immediate change will occur
on the market from the new trading regulations, as investors are
already too skittish and gloomy because of the country's economic
crash and poor corporate earnings prospects.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that foreign investors are not expected to see the
rule changes as new incentives to enter the market, considering
the present overall market and exchange risks.
</P>
<P>
Last week the SET index mostly stayed just a few points below
the 400-points mark, the lowest level since the SET was founded
two decades ago. On Friday, the SET index was 395.47 points, down
3.96 points from the previous day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
