<HEADLINE> Ecuador Elects New Assembly to Reform Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, November 30 (Xinhua) -- Ecuadorans went to the polls
today for a temporary National Assembly that will reform the
country's constitution.
</P>
<P>
The Ecuadorans chose 70 assembly deputies from 1,500 candidates
of the seven political parties and 22 independent movements. The
preliminary results will be released Monday and the final ones in
about a week.
</P>
<P>
The major tasks of the new assembly will be to write a new
constitution, debate the dissolution of Congress, the creation of
a Senate and setting the rules for the privatization of state
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
About 42 percent of Ecuador's seven million eligible voters did
not take part in the votes.
</P>
<P>
According to the pre-election polls, the opposition Social
Christian Party would gain most seats in the assembly.
</P>
<P>
The assembly will start working on December 20 and will be
disbanded in February. 
</P>
