<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila, Muslim Rebels to Sign Peace Pact Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and
the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) have agreed to sign
a preliminary peace agreement by Christmas, and a final peace
treaty before June 30 next year, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
This agreement was reached Saturday during a meeting in central
Mindanao between the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Jose
de Venecia, and the MILF vice chairman for military affairs,
Mohammad al-Haj Murad, the national newspaper Today said.
</P>
<P>
Murad was quoted as saying after the meeting that he agreed in
principle the timetable and confirmed the advanced stage of the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Murad headed the MILF panel that held talks in the largest MILF
stronghold, Camp Abubakar, with de Venecia and his party, which
included Orlando Soriano, chief government negotiator in peace
talks with the MILF.
</P>
<P>
"We are extremely optimistic about reaching a preliminary
understanding before Christmas this year to advance the ongoing
peace process," de Venecia was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under the preliminary agreement, the MILF-controlled areas in
central and western Mindanao will be transformed into special
development zone, another newspaper Malaya reported.
</P>
<P>
Malaya quoted Murad as saying the MILF leadership will meet
from December 15 to 17 to finalize its position in preparation for
the next round of peace talks with the government panel on
December 22 and 23.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and the government started their exploratory peace
talks in January this year, and reached a breakthrough in July
when both sides signed a comprehensive ceasefire in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
During the last round of peace talks in November, the two sides
signed an accord on principles and rules for implementing the
truce agreement, laying the groundwork for further mutual
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway faction of the mainstream Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF), which had already signed a peace accord
with Manila in September last year.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, who has sought to establish a separate Islamic state
in Mindanao, refused to be included in the MNLF-Manila peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is currently the largest Muslim rebel force in the
country, with an estimated 12,000 fighters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Pakistan's Constitutional Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The current constitutional
crisis in Pakistan seems to be worsening as the president and the
prime minister are now openly on a collision path.
</P>
<P>
A power tussle between President Farooq Leghari and Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif assumed new proportions last night when
Sharif openly accused the Presidency of "not extending assistance
in the parliament's efforts to preserve constitution."
</P>
<P>
In his 25-minute televised speech to the nation, Sharif said
his government passed Amendment in the Contempt of Court Law to
steer the country out of the further crisis but the president
refused to sign it.
</P>
<P>
"Crisis could be averted if the president signed the bill.
However, he (Leghari) refused to sign the law, passed by the two
houses of the Parliament."
</P>
<P>
The parliament passed the bill on November 18 in an apparent
effort to protect Sharif who was formally charged with contempt of
the court the next day by a Supreme Court bench led by Chief
Justice Sajjad Ali Shah.
</P>
<P>
The bill was forwarded on November 18 to Leghari, who has a
maximum of 30 days to sign it. However, there has been no response
from him.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said that the political situation in this south
Asian nation is worsening when the two constitutional heads -- the
president and the prime minister -- refuse to co-exist contrary to
the demand of the prevalent political system.
</P>
<P>
The two exchanged strongly-worded letters following an assault
last Friday by hundreds of demonstrators on the Supreme Court
where a five-judge bench led by Chief Justice Sajjad was hearing a
petition against the prime minister on the alleged contempt of the
court.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Justice asked the president to provide army's
protection for the Supreme Court building and its judges.
</P>
<P>
It was in this context that Leghari wrote a letter to Sharif,
advising him to "immediately ask the Pakistan Army to provide
security cover to the Supreme Court building and to provide safety
and protection to the judges and their residences."
</P>
<P>
Leghari also asked Sharif to initiate proceedings for
misconduct against Justice Saeed Uzzaman Siddiqui, the third most
senior judge in the Supreme Court who has called for a full-court
hearing against the controversial appointment of the Chief
Justice.
</P>
<P>
However, Leghari's two pieces of advice were rejected by
Sharif.
</P>
<P>
In his reply, Sharif accused Leghari of taking sides with the
judiciary in the on-going constitutional crisis involving the
country's executive and the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
"There is surely no justification for making such an extreme
request (for army protection). In fact arrangements for adequate
security have already been made," Sharif said.
</P>
<P>
"I also regret your request for proceedings to be initiated
against Saeed Uzzaman Siddiqui merely because that is the demand
of Justice Sajjad Ali Shah," he wrote to Leghari.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the grave constitutional crisis took another
dimension as two conflicting schedules were issued for today's
Supreme Court proceedings.
</P>
<P>
One schedule suggested the holding of a five-member bench to
hear the contempt of court case against Sharif and others, while
the other said a full court comprising 15 judges will hear the
pending cases against the appointment of Chief Justice Sajjad.
</P>
<P>
The Chief Justice issued an order Sunday evening cancelling the
full court meeting to hear a constitutional petition against him.
</P>
<P>
However, hours after the Chief Justice's order, Justice
Siddiqui issued a press release saying he declined to accept
Sajjad's order because it "amounts to interference with judicial
process."
</P>
<P>
There in fact exist two supreme courts: one headed by Chief
Justice Sajjad and the other by Justice Siddiqui. Both are
scheduled to meet today as official notifications for the two
meetings have already been issued.
</P>
<P>
The judicial confusion has further complicated the political
situation in the country, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
While the differences between Leghari and Sharif have come out
into the open, the president, whom the government has indirectly
held responsible for the current crisis, has remained silent.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers have printed stories about the government's
plans to impeach the president, but the two have refrained from
assailing each other directly.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts believed that the president and the prime
minister are heading for a showdown after the two made their
divergent positions public in their exchange of letters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
