<HEADLINE> Italian Ruling Coalition Wins Elections in Key Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 30 (Xinhua) - Candidates of Italy's ruling
Olive Tree coalition government won elections for mayor in some
major cities Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Exit polls showed that Olive Tree coalition candidate, Giuseppe
Periccu, won 53.5 percent of the votes in the northern city of
Genoa where the first-round voting took place on November 16.
</P>
<P>
Leoluca Orlando, the incumbent mayor of the Sicilian city of
Palermo, gained 56-60 percent of the ballots and hailed the result
as excellent.
</P>
<P>
Orlando has been credited with transforming the city, fighting
against Sicilian mafia and raising the city's profile at home and
abroad.
</P>
<P>
Coalition candidates have already won the first-round local
elections in such major cities as Rome, Naples and Venice.
</P>
<P>
In mainland Italy, coalition candidates' key rivals were
Freedom Alliance or Northern League in the second round run-offs.
</P>
<P>
Some 6 million eligible voters were to cast their ballots in the
second round of elections for mayors of 43 communal councils in
mainland Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
