<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weaker Peso Raises Philippine Debt Payments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- Payments by the Philippines on
its foreign debts this year are projected to rise by 16 percent
owing to the depreciated peso and rising interest rates abroad.
</P>
<P>
In a government document published today, the country's foreign
debt payments are seen to rise to 5.8 billion U.S. dollars this
year, compared with 5 billion dollars paid last year.
</P>
<P>
The document said interest payments were particularly higher in
the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The currency crisis, which has weakened the peso by as much as
30 percent since July, has made it more expensive for the country
to pay off its foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
Of the projected external debt service this year, about 57
percent or 3.3 billion dollars will go to the payment for the
principal of the debts while the balance of 2.5 billion dollars
will be paid for the interest.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the country paid some 2.72
billion dollars in foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
The document also showed that foreign debt payments by the
country's private and public sectors are seen to average between
5.9 billion dollars and 7 billion dollars annually in the next
five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
