<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard stepped up pressure on the Senate
yesterday to fix the native title issue immediately, appealing
directly in his first national address for community support for
the government's Wik bill. The bill, which the government is
determined to push through the Senate, is regarded by Australian
aboriginal leaders as unfair to the aborigines.
</P>
<P>
-- The Australian Defense Force will dramatically upgrade its
air and naval strike and self-defense capabilities under a
multi-billion dollar plan to be outlined tomorrow in the federal
government's first strategic policy document.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Searing summer temperatures, severe flooding and mudslides
will become common over vast tracts of North Asia, Latin America
and Africa if carbon dioxide levels are not controlled within 50
years, a Japanese-Australian study has found.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Papua New Guinea's five month-old coalition government was
yesterday on the verge of falling apart, split by bribery
allegations and claims of backstabbing, which led to the sacking
of two key ministers by Prime Minister Bill Skate.
</P>
