<HEADLINE> Safeguarding Foreign Citizen's Rights Noted in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
has stepped up an education campaign resently on the Vienna
Convention to remind the nation's law-enforcement officials that
foreign citizens arrested have the right to let their government
know it.
</P>
<P>
The campaign was renewed following periodic complaints from
diplomatic officials and defense lawyers that many law-enforcement
agents in the United States know little or nothing about the
treaty, The New York Times said today.
</P>
<P>
Under the Vienna Convention on Consular Relations, ratified by
more than 160 countries including the United States, foreign
nationals taken into custody in one country must be told that they
can notify their home country's embassy or local consulate. In
some cases, embassies must be notified of such arrests
automatically.
</P>
<P>
The United States embassies rely on the treaty as a critical
protection for American citizens in trouble with the law abroad.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Mexican government lodged formal
complaints to the U.S. State Department this year that the latter
had not inform it the arrests and execution of a number of Mexican
citizens in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Recently the State Department briefed about 100 police chiefs
and other law-enforcement agents in Texas State about the right of
foreign citizens under the Vienna Convention.
</P>
<P>
Those who were briefed also received a brochure that explained:
"When foreign nationals are arrested or detained, they must be
advised of the right to have their consular officials notified,"
the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More U.S. Cities Use Youth Curfews: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, November 30 (Xinhua) -- More cities in the United
States are using nighttime and daytime youth curfews to reduce
crime and truancy.
</P>
<P>
A survey to be released here Monday by the U.S. Conference of
Mayors found that 276 of 347 responding cities had a nighttime
curfew. Seventy-six had a daytime curfew as well, The Associated
Press reported.
</P>
<P>
A similar survey the mayors group did in 1995 showed 270 of 387
cities had a nightly curfew.
</P>
<P>
"Curfews are not the end-all. It's just one tool in the
toolbox," said Louisville Mayor Jerry Abramson, chairman of the
mayors' conference task force on youth violence.
</P>
<P>
Abramson said curfews should be just one part of a juvenile
crime prevention.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, 56 percent, or 154, of the surveyed
cities have had a youth curfew for at least 10 years. Officials in
half these cities say juvenile crime has dropped since the curfew
was imposed, 11 percent say the number of juvenile crimes has
remained steady, and 10 percent have had an increase in
juvenile-related crime. Because most of the remaining cities have
had curfews for only a short time, no data on the impact on
juvenile crime was available.
</P>
<P>
The most important reason for a daytime curfew is to ensure
teens go to school, but Abramson said there are financial
incentives as well. State education funding typically is based on
attendance, he noted, and truancy can cost a school system
millions of dollars in lost revenue.
</P>
<P>
But curfews can be expensive for cities, too. Twenty-three
percent, or 61, of the cities said there were increased costs to
enforce curfews.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-three percent of cities reported problems implementing
the curfew.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen cities said there had been constitutional challenges
to the curfew. The American Civil Liberties Union has fought such
laws in a number of cities on the grounds that they impinge on
liberties guaranteed by the Bill of Rights. It suggests cities use
the money spent enforcing curfews on youth programs instead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
