<DOCNO> XIE19971201.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Aid Worker Killed in Tajikistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 30 (Xinhua) -- A 28-year-old French aid worker
who was taken hostage by Tajik rebels was killed today in an army
operation to free her and her friend, said reports from
Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
Karine Mane, 28, who worked for the United Nations High Commission
for Refugees and for a European program for helping street
children in former Soviet republics, was kidnapped on November 18
in her home in Dushanbe by an armed group commanded by Rizvon
Sadirov, who asked for the release of the latter's brother Bakhrom
Sadirov, imprisoned for terrorism.
</P>
<P>
According to the Tajik Foreign Ministry, the Tajik army
intervened to liberate Mane and her friend, Franck Janier-Dubry,
after the kidnappers hardened their conditions for releasing them.
Janier-Dubry was freed safe and sound.
</P>
<P>
The French government immediately expressed sadness over the
death of Mane, and President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin sent messages of condolences to the family of Mane.
</P>
<P>
A French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman said that there is no
reason to think that the Tajik authorities have not done all they
could to have the two hostages freed safe and sound.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said that he was not
sure about the conditions under which Mane was killed during the
army operation.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the death of Mane "posed the question on the
conditions under which are exposed sometimes the people who are
carried by a magnificent ideal within the framework of
non-governmental organizations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
